es of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Critically endangered flora of Asia]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Dipterocarpaceae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shorea_zeylanica"}
{"title_page": "1890\u201391 British Home Championship", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox international football competition\n|tourney_name=1890\u201391 British Home Championship\n|image      =\n|size       =\n|caption    =\n|country    =England, Ireland, Scotland and Wales\n|dates      =7 February\u20136 April 1891\n|num_teams  =4\n|champion   =ENG\n|count      =3\n|second     =SCO\n|attendance =\n|matches    =6\n|goals      =46\n|top_scorer ={{fbicon|IRE}} [[Olphie Stanfield]] {{nowrap|(5 goals)}}\n|prevseason =[[1889\u201390 British Home Championship|1889\u201390]]\n|nextseason =[[1891\u201392 British Home Championship|1891\u201392]]\n}}\nThe '''1890\u201391 [[British Home Championship]]''' was an international [[football (soccer)|football]] tournament between the British [[Home Nations]]. Despite strong showings from all four teams, [[England national football team|England]] eventually won the trophy with victories in all three games including, as at the [[1890 British Home Championship|1890]] and [[1892 British Home Championship|1892]] competitions, matches against [[Wales national football team|Wales]] and [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]] played simultaneously. Ireland notched up one of their highest ever wins, 7\u20132 over Wales, but still only finished third, whilst the Welsh ran [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] close in their encounter, but ultimately scored zero points.\n\nScotland and Ireland began the tournament with the Scots securing a narrow win in [[Glasgow]]. They extended their lead in [[Wrexham]] despite Wales playing well and nearly taking a draw, eventually going down 3\u20134. England then played their double on 7 March, scoring an aggregate of 10\u20132 as both the amateur and professional sides easily won their games over Wales and Ireland. Ireland and Wales played for pride in their final game, Ireland routing the Welsh in Belfast and finishing five goals ahead. In the tournament decider in [[Blackburn]], England were too strong for the Scots in a close game and the result was an England victory, giving them the trophy undisputed.\n\n==Table==\n<onlyinclude>{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|show_positions=n\n|winpoints=2\n\n|team1=ENG|name_ENG={{fb|ENG}}\n|team2=SCO|name_SCO={{fb|SCO}}\n|team3=IRE|name_IRE={{fb|IRE}}\n|team4=WAL|name_WAL={{fb|WAL|1807}}\n|win_ENG=3|draw_ENG=0|loss_ENG=0|gf_ENG=12|ga_ENG=3|status_ENG=C\n|win_SCO=2|draw_SCO=0|loss_SCO=1|gf_SCO=7|ga_SCO=6\n|win_IRE=1|draw_IRE=0|loss_IRE=2|gf_IRE=9|ga_IRE=10\n|win_WAL=0|draw_WAL=0|loss_WAL=3|gf_WAL=6|ga_WAL=15\n\n|col_C=#ccffcc|text_C=\n|result1=C\n|update=complete|source=\n|class_rules = 1) points. The points system worked as follows: 2 points for a win and 1 point for a draw.\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n==Results==\n{{football box \n | date = 7 February 1891\n | team1 = {{fb-rt|IRE}}\n | score = 7 \u2013 2\n | team2 = {{fb|WAL|1807}}\n | goals1 = [[William Boyd Dalton|William Dalton]] {{goal|19}}<br />[[Olphie Stanfield]] {{goal|22||34||42||80}}<br />[[George Gaffikin]] {{goal|60}}<br />[[Sam Torrans]] {{goal|63}}\n | goals2 = {{goal|10}} [[Robert Roberts (footballer, born 1865)|Robert Roberts]]<br />{{goal|37}} [[Albert Thomas Davies|Albert Davies]]\n | stadium = [[Ulsterville]], [[Belfast]]  \n | attendance = 12,000\n | referee = Robert F. Harrison ([[Scottish Football Association|Scotland]])\n}}\n----\n{{football box \n | date = 7 March 1891\n | team1 = {{fb-rt|ENG}}\n | score = 6 \u2013 1\n | team2 = {{fb|IRE}}\n | goals1 = [[Tinsley Lindley]] 2<br />[[Billy Bassett]]<br />[[George Cotterill]]<br />[[Arthur Henfrey]]<br />[[Harry Daft]]\n | goals2 = [[Tommy Whiteside]]\n | stadium = [[Molineux Stadium|Molineux]], [[Wolverhampton]] \n | attendance = 15,231\n | referee = Richard Gough ([[Welsh Football Association|Wales]])\n}}\n----\n{{football box \n | date = 7 March 1891\n | team1 = {{fb-rt|ENG}}\n | score = 4 \u2013 1\n | team2 = {{fb|WAL|1807}}\n | goals1 = [[Johnny Go