Trollh\u00e4ttan Municipality]], Sweden.\n* [[Dragon International Film Studios|Valleywood]] is the informal name for the Dragon International film studio complex in Wales.\n\n===Oceania===\n* [[Wellywood]] refers to [[Wellington]], [[New Zealand]] - home of [[Weta Workshop]], [[Weta Digital]] and [[Peter Jackson]]'s film studio.\n* Mollywood is sometimes jokingly used to describe the [[Hollywood Sign]]-inspired town name on the hillside at the eastern edge of [[Mosgiel]] in New Zealand.<ref>[http://www.nzherald.co.nz/travel/news/article.cfm?c_id=7&objectid=11297406 \"Kia ora: Mosgiel\"], Jul 25, 2014, NZ Herald</ref>\n* Aussiewood or Oziwood refers to [[Cinema of Australia|Australian cinema]], including [[Ozploitation]] from the 1970s and 1980s but post-dates the genre.\n\n==Other==\nSome Hollywood-inspired nicknames do not refer directly to the film industry:\n* [[Dollywood]] is an amusement park owned by [[Dolly Parton]]. \n* FC Hollywood is a nickname for [[FC Bayern Munich]], used especially widely by German media in the 1990s, an era in which Bayern players were as likely to appear in gossip pages as in sports pages.\n==See also==\n{{portal|Lists}}\n* [[Borehamwood]]\n* [[Lists of nicknames]] \u2013 nickname list articles on Wikipedia\n\n==References ==\n{{reflist}}\n* \n\n[[Category:Hollywood history and culture]]\n[[Category:Lists of regional nicknames|Hollywood]]\n", "name_user": "Ariharan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Hollywood-inspired_nicknames"}
{"title_page": "American University of Malta", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n| name              = American University of Malta\n| native_name       = <!-- SOURCE?? Universit\u00e0 Amerikana ta' Malta -->\n| native_name_lang  = mt\n| image             = Dock no. 1.jpg\n| caption           = Renovation works at the Cospicua campus in November 2016\n| former_name       = American Institute of Malta\n| type              = [[Private university|Private]]\n| established       = {{start date and age|2016|09|16|df=y}}<ref name=\"ourbeginnings\"/>\n| founder           = Sadeen Education Investment Ltd.\n| provost           = Jeremy Brown\n| students          = 143<ref>{{cite news |last1=Micallef |first1=Keith |title=AUM student population is a fifth of promised number |url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/aum-student-population-fifth-of-promised-number.746091 |work=[[Times of Malta]] |date=31 October 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191031205710/https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/aum-student-population-fifth-of-promised-number.746091 |archivedate=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n| city              = [[Cospicua]]\n| country           = [[Malta]]\n| coordinates       = {{Coord|35|52|55|N|14|31|11.2|E|display=inline, title}}\n| website           = [http://www.aum.edu.mt/ aum.edu.mt]\n| logo              = American University of Malta logo.png\n}}\n\nThe '''American University of Malta''' ('''AUM''') is a [[private university|private]], American-style [[liberal arts college]] in [[Cospicua]], [[Malta]]. The establishment of the educational institution was announced in May 2015, and the project was originally intended to regenerate the South of Malta and give said area an economic and social boost.<ref name=opm-presentation/> Since the proposal was announced, Dock 1 in Cospicua was chosen for the head campus, while extensions are being planned for other sites in Cospicua and \u017bonqor, [[Marsaskala]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Muscat|first1=Caroline|title=Mounting opposition to use of ODZ land|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150514/local/mounting-opposition-to-use-of-odz-land.568095|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=14 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220233523/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150514/local/mounting-opposition-to-use-of-odz-land.568095|archivedate=20 December 2015}}</ref> It was officially established on 16 September 2016,<ref name=\"ourbeginnings\"/> and it opened in September 2017.<ref name=\"maltachamber\"/>\n\n==Planning and Opening==\nOn 5 May 2015, the [[Jordan]]ian construction company Sadeen Group and the [[Government of Malta]] signed an agreement at [[Auberge de Castille]] for the former to set up a private educational institution called the American University of Malta (AUM). Initially the university was planned to be located in [[Spain]], but the owner of Sadeen, Hani Salah, was persuaded to establish it in Malta by then-Prime Minister of Malta [[Joseph Muscat]].\n\nThe university was intended to accommodate 4000 students, primarily from the [[Middle East]], [[North Africa]] and [[Europe]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/heads-of-agreement-for-4000-student-american-university-expected-on.566504|title=Heads of agreement for 4,000-student American university expected on Tuesday|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=2015-09-12}}</ref> However, the university has consistently failed to meet its recruitment goals.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Micallef|first1=Keith|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/aum-student-population-fifth-of-promised-number.746091|title=AUM student population is a fifth of promised number|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=30 October 2019}}</ref> By the time all campuses are complete, it is intended to have schools of business, architecture and design, engineering, arts, sciences, and information technology, each offering one or more Bachelor Degree Programs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aum.edu.mt/bachelors-degree-programs/|title=Undergraduate Degree Programs|website=aum.edu.mt|date=1 January 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe original curricula of the AUM were provided by the [[DePaul University]]. The latter claims that it did not commit financial or human resources to the AUM, and it was not involved in any discussions with the Government of Malta.<ref>{{cite news|title=DePaul University denies involvement in site selection for proposed American University of Malta|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150508/local/depaul-university-denies-involvement-in-site-selection-for-proposed.567368|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=8 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913161255/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150508/local/depaul-university-denies-involvement-in-site-selection-for-proposed.567368|archivedate=13 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Mathews|first1=Kristin Claes|title=Faculty create curricula for American University of Malta|url=http://www.depaulnewsline.com/features/faculty-create-curricula-american-university-malta|work=DePaul Newsline|date=13 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150520003229/http://www.depaulnewsline.com/features/faculty-create-curricula-american-university-malta|archivedate=20 May 2015}}</ref> However, a member of DePaul's executive administrative team, Khaled El Zayyat, became the AUM's first Vice President of Global Initiatives: \"El Zayyat previously held teaching and administrative posts at DePaul University, Chicago, and supervised dual degree graduate programmes for DePaul University in Jordan.\" <ref>{{cite blog|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=When is a university not a university? (1)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/06/when-is-a-university-not-a-university-1/|website=manueldelia.com|date=June 4, 2019}}</ref> El Zayyat initially hired and supervised IT staff at the AUM. Two months after the IT Administrator who reported to El Zayyat, David Aquilina, was dismissed, the Maltese government hired the same individual to work in an identical capacity in the Office of the Prime Minister. \n\nThe university was originally intended to create a social and economic boost to localities in the [[South Eastern Region]] of Malta, which is regarded as being less developed than the rest of the island.<ref name=opm-presentation>{{cite web|title=Investiment g\u0127an-na\u0127a t'isfel ta' Malta \u2013 American University of Malta|url=https://opm.gov.mt/en/Documents/AUM/AUM%20PRESENTATION.pdf|website=[[Government of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304213220/https://opm.gov.mt/en/Documents/AUM/AUM%20PRESENTATION.pdf|archivedate=4 March 2016|language=Maltese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Estimation of the Contribution to the Maltese Economy of the Development and Operation of an International Higher Academic Institution: Update Based on a Project Proposal Spread Over Two Sites|url=https://opm.gov.mt/en/Documents/AUM/AUM-EIA.pdf|website=[[Government of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703110407/https://opm.gov.mt/en/Documents/AUM/AUM-EIA.pdf|archivedate=3 July 2016}}</ref> The project has an investment of over \u20ac115 million, and it was intended to create around 400<ref name=\"opm-presentation\" /> to 750 jobs.<ref name=\"MT0516\">{{cite news|url=http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/64924/american_university_of_malta_campus_to_take_three_years_to_complete#.V3jwKfl961s|title='American University of Malta' campus to take three years to complete|last1=Dalli|first1=Miriam|date=6 May 2016|work=[[Malta Today]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604130547/http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/64924/american_university_of_malta_campus_to_take_three_years_to_complete|archivedate=4 June 2016}}</ref> The project's estimated economic output was speculated to be about \u20ac48 to \u20ac85 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160921/local/sadeens-five-year-licence-dictated-by-law.625667|title=Sadeen\u2019s five-year licence 'dictated by law'|last1=Sansone|first1=Kurt|date=21 September 2016|work=[[Times of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922140626/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160921/local/sadeens-five-year-licence-dictated-by-law.625667|archivedate=22 September 2016}}</ref> As of September 2016, demand for property in Cospicua reportedly increased as a result of the university project.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bartolo|first1=Janice|title=Xhieda li l-American University of Malta bdiet tag\u0127ti spinta lin-na\u0127a t'isfel ta' Malta|url=http://www.one.com.mt/news/xhieda-li-l-american-university-of-malta-bdiet-taghti-spinta-lin-naha-tisfel-ta-malta/|work=[[One Productions|One]]|date=27 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019133208/http://www.one.com.mt/news/xhieda-li-l-american-university-of-malta-bdiet-taghti-spinta-lin-naha-tisfel-ta-malta/|archivedate=19 October 2016|language=Maltese}}</ref> Also, concerns have arisen that the university's presence threatens the heritage and quality of life in the Bormla community and Three Cities region.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Vella|first1=Matthew|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/environment/townscapes/97245/cottonera_activists_urge_residents_to_petition_against_aum_extension#.XXN4fPZuLIU|title=Cottonera activists urge residents to petition against AUM extension|work=MaltaToday|date=3 September 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/cottonera-residents-unite-against-over-development.736955|title=Cottonera residents unite against over-development|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=22 September 2019}}</ref>\n  \nThe university originally planned to take in its first students on October 2016, with lectures at [[SmartCity Malta]] until the head campus was completed.<ref name=times2015-08-20/> The beginning of the first academic year was later moved to 28 August 2017, with lectures held at the Dock No. 1 campus in Cospicua.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sansone|first1=Kurt|title=Lectures at AUM to start on August 28|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160925/local/lectures-at-aum-to-start-on-august-28.625991|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=25 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160926154655/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160925/local/lectures-at-aum-to-start-on-august-28.625991|archivedate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, [[John Ryder (scholar)|John Ryder]] was named as the head of the American University of Malta, assuming the dual roles of Provost and Acting Vice President of the AUM. Ryder's qualifications for the post included a terminal academic degree in Philosophy and two-years' experience as president of Khazar University in Azerbaijan <ref>{{cite news|title=Former Baku university rector to head 'American Institute of Malta'|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160127/local/former-baku-university-rector-to-head-american-institute-of-malta.600270|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=26 January 2016}}</ref>     \n\n===Location of campus and use of ODZ land===\n[[File:Site for the future American Institute of Malta.jpeg|thumb|\u017bonqor Point, where part of the university campus is to be built]]\n\nWhen the university project was announced in May 2015, the government offered the Sadeen Group {{convert|90000|m2|abbr=on}} of Outside Development Zone (ODZ) land near \u017bonqor Point in [[Marsaskala]] on which to build the university. A natural park, partially funded by the university, would be set up nearby. The proposal to use ODZ land raised concerns among environmentalists, including the NGOs [[Flimkien g\u0127al Ambjent A\u0127jar]], [[Friends of the Earth (Malta)|Friends of the Earth Malta]], Ramblers Association, [[Din l-Art \u0126elwa]], NatureTrust Malta, [[Birdlife]] Malta, Malta Organic Agriculture Movement and Greenhouse. The Malta Developers Association also stated that a better site should be found,<ref name=times2015-05-05>{{cite news|title=Fort San Leonardo may be incorporated in new university campus|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150505/local/update-3-fort-san-leonardo-may-be-incorporated-in-new-university.566883|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=5 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928173056/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150505/local/update-3-fort-san-leonardo-may-be-incorporated-in-new-university.566883|archivedate=28 September 2015}}</ref> while the Church criticized the process used to select the land for the university.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Muscat|first1=Caroline|title=Church slams government\u2019s handling of university bid|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150521/local/church-slams-governments-handling-of-university-bid.569018|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=21 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220213628/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150521/local/church-slams-governments-handling-of-university-bid.569018|archivedate=20 December 2015}}</ref> Meanwhile, residents of Marsaskala and southern Malta supported the university project by signing a petition in its favour.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tan-nofsinhar ji\u0121bru petizzjoni favur il-pro\u0121ett tal-universit\u00e0|url=http://www.inewsmalta.com/dart/20150615-tan-nofsinhar-ji-bru-petizzjoni-favur-il-pro-ett-tal-universit|work=iNews Malta|date=16 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618014128/http://www.inewsmalta.com/dart/20150615-tan-nofsinhar-ji-bru-petizzjoni-favur-il-pro-ett-tal-universit|archivedate=18 June 2015|language=Maltese}}</ref> \n\nThe government initially planned to include the 19th-century [[Fort Leonardo]] within the university campus. Prime Minister Joseph Muscat also stated that constructing the university in Marsaskala would pressure the owners of the former [[Jerma Palace Hotel]] to redevelop the site, which has fallen into disrepair since being closed down in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dalli|first1=Kim|title=University plan \u2018puts pressure on Jerma site\u2019|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150506/local/university-plan-puts-pressure-on-jerma-site.566951|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=6 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929031031/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150506/local/university-plan-puts-pressure-on-jerma-site.566951|archivedate=29 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nMuscat responded to the environmentalists' criticism by stating that the [[Malta Environment and Planning Authority]] would consider other sites as long as they are located in the southern part of the island.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Martin|first1=Ivan|title=\u2018University will generate \u20ac25m a year\u2019|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150504/local/university-will-generate-25m-a-year.566645|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=4 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220195817/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150504/local/university-will-generate-25m-a-year.566645|archivedate=20 December 2015}}</ref> A public consultation process was subsequently made in order to select an alternative site for the university campus.<ref>{{cite web|title=The American University of Malta \u2013 Preliminary Alternative Sites Evaluation Report|url=https://opm.gov.mt/en/Documents/AUM/Preliminary%20Alternative%20Sites%20Evaluation%20Report.pdf|website=[[Government of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304214404/https://opm.gov.mt/en/Documents/AUM/Preliminary%20Alternative%20Sites%20Evaluation%20Report.pdf|archivedate=4 March 2016|date=August 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 May 2015, the Front \u0126arsien ODZ ([[Maltese language|Maltese]] for ''Front for the Protection of ODZ'') was set up in response to the proposed development at \u017bonqor Point. The group aims to protect all ODZ land in Malta, and it includes then-[[Labour Party (Malta)|Labour]] MP, turned [[Democratic Party (Malta)|Democratic Party]] (PD) members, [[Marlene Farrugia]], [[Whip (politics)|government whip]] Godfrey Farrugia and former [[Alternattiva Demokratika]] politician, turned Nationalist Party (PN) member, [[Michael Briguglio]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Neil|title=Godfrey, Marlene Farrugia join 'Front Harsien ODZ,' group says Zonqor project can be stopped|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2015-05-23/local-news/Front-Harsien-ODZ-launched-not-just-against-Zonqor-university-but-all-other-ODZ-developments-6736136030|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=23 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150811133750/http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2015-05-23/local-news/Front-Harsien-ODZ-launched-not-just-against-Zonqor-university-but-all-other-ODZ-developments-6736136030|archivedate=11 August 2015}}</ref> On 20 June, the front held a protest in [[Valletta]] against the development, and it was attended by 3000 people.<ref>{{cite news|title=Government announces reduced university plans for Zonqor|url=http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/56337/government_announces_reduced_university_plans_for_zonqor_#.VncO4PkrLIV|work=[[Malta Today]]|date=20 August 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010090820/http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/56337/government_announces_reduced_university_plans_for_zonqor_|archivedate=10 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 August, Muscat announced that the government had reached an agreement with the Sadeen Group that the campus be split between the former [[Malta Dockyard|Dock No. 1]] in [[Cospicua]] and a reduced site at \u017bonqor Point. The campus at \u017bonqor is much smaller than the one originally planned, and it will occupy the site of the water polo pitch and {{convert|18000|m2|abbr=on}} of adjoining ODZ fields. This campus is to consist of three faculties and student dormitories, with a maximum height of five stories. A new water polo pitch is also to be built to replace the one that will be demolished to make way for the university. The campus at Cospicua will occupy two former [[warehouse]]s at Dock No. 1 which were built during [[Knights Hospitaller|Hospitaller]] and [[British Empire|British]] rule. Additional buildings are to be constructed, but they are to keep with the architectural style of the area.<ref name=times2015-08-20>{{cite news|title='American' University to occupy Dock 1 buildings and reduced Zonqor site|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150820/local/update-3-american-university-to-occupy-dock-1-buildings-and-reduced.581335|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=20 August 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911141423/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150820/local/update-3-american-university-to-occupy-dock-1-buildings-and-reduced.581335|archivedate=11 September 2015}}</ref> This restoration project is bringing an otherwise run down Dock no. 1 back on its feet, which had been abandoned with the end of the rule of the British. The government will rent out both campuses to Sadeen Group for around \u20ac200,000 a year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Government to rent public land to American University of Malta on the cheap|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2015-08-30/local-news/Government-to-rent-public-land-to-American-University-of-Malta-on-the-cheap-6736141281|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=30 August 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016154148/http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2015-08-30/local-news/Government-to-rent-public-land-to-American-University-of-Malta-on-the-cheap-6736141281|archivedate=16 October 2015}}</ref> \n\nFront \u0126arsien ODZ said that the proposal of splitting the campus was better than the original one, but said that it was still unacceptable to build on ODZ land.<ref name=times2015-08-20/> The [[University Students' Council (Malta)|University Students' Council]] also expressed its disappointment at the government building part of the campus at \u017bonqor Point.<ref>{{cite news|title=KSU disappointed by the governments adamant decision confirming the American University of Malta at Zonqor Point|url=http://www.ksu.org.mt/index.php/press/160-ksu-disappointed-by-the-governments-adamant-decision-confirming-the-american-university-of-malta-at-zonqor-point|work=[[University Students' Council (Malta)|KSU]]|date=28 September 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220212200/http://www.ksu.org.mt/index.php/press/160-ksu-disappointed-by-the-governments-adamant-decision-confirming-the-american-university-of-malta-at-zonqor-point|archivedate=20 December 2015}}</ref> On the other hand, the move was welcomed by the Cospicua Heritage Society, who said that the [[Three Cities]] and [[Kalkara]] would greatly benefit from the project.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cospicua Heritage Society qed tappo\u0121\u0121ja l-pro\u0121ett tal-universit\u00e0|url=http://www.inewsmalta.com/dart/20150824-cospicua-heritage-society-qed-tappo-ja-pro-ett-tal-universit|work=iNews Malta|date=24 August 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220234715/http://www.inewsmalta.com/dart/20150824-cospicua-heritage-society-qed-tappo-ja-pro-ett-tal-universit|archivedate=20 December 2015|language=Maltese}}</ref>\n\nThe government approved the granting of land for the AUM after a 15-hour long debate in parliament on 15 December 2015.<ref name=times2015-12-15>{{cite news|title=House approves 'American University' property motion after night-long debate|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20151215/local/aum-undergoing-rigorous-evaluation-education-minister.595847|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=15 December 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151219174151/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20151215/local/aum-undergoing-rigorous-evaluation-education-minister.595847|archivedate=19 December 2015}}</ref> Front \u0126arsien ODZ called this parliamentary sitting \"surreal\" and said that it shows terrible governance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Front slams vote for 'American University'|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20151216/local/front-slams-vote-for-american-university.595918|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=16 December 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151219175001/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20151216/local/front-slams-vote-for-american-university.595918|archivedate=19 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Malta - Cospicua - Fuq San l-Inkurunazzjoni - Dock no1 11 ies.jpg|thumb|The British Building at Dock No. 1 in Cospicua]]\n\nOn 25 August 2016, the Planning Authority approved the restoration of the British Building at Dock No. 1, and its conversion into a campus to house part of the AUM. Parts of the building which were destroyed during [[World War II]] will be rebuilt, while an intermediate level and a new second floor with a [[Contemporary architecture|contemporary]] glass-and-steel design will be constructed.<ref>{{cite web|title=University in Cospicua granted permit|url=http://www.pa.org.mt/news-details?id=1137|website=Planning Authority|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828114710/http://www.pa.org.mt/news-details?id=1137|archivedate=28 August 2016|date=25 August 2016}}</ref> The renovation of the building was entrusted to the architect Edwin Mintoff, to be completed by April 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Saliba|first1=Norma|title=American University buildings will reflect the past historic appearance of Cospicua Wharf|url=http://www.tvm.com.mt/en/news/il-binjiet-tal-uaameamerican-university-buildings-will-reflect-the-past-historic-appearance-of-cospicua-wharfrican-university-buildings-will-reflect-the-past-historic-appearance-of-cospicua-wharfm-se/|work=[[TVM (Malta)|TVM]]|date=26 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nThere are plans to restore the Knights' Building at Dock No. 1 and convert it into part of the campus, and this renovation is planned to be completed by 2017\u201318. The Marsaskala campus is to be ready by 2019\u201320.<ref name=\"times2016-09-25\"/>\n\n===Accreditation and licensing===\nIn December 2015, Leader of the Opposition [[Simon Busuttil]] stated that since the AUM applied for the licence of a \"Higher Education Institution\", its marketing of itself as a \"University\" is illegal.<ref name=times2015-12-15/> In January 2016, the National Commission for Further and Higher Education announced that Sadeen Education Investment Ltd had been given a licence to operate a Higher Education Institution under the name ''American Institute of Malta''. This was the first step in the process to acquire a university licence.<ref name=times2016-01-26>{{cite news|title=American University of Malta formally becomes American Institute of Malta, process to acquire university licence in process|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160126/local/american-university-of-malta-formally-becomes-american-institute-of.600155|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=26 January 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126174313/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160126/local/american-university-of-malta-formally-becomes-american-institute-of.600155|archivedate=26 January 2016}}</ref> The commission has stated that a degree issued by the American Institute would have the same value as one issued by the University of Malta.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ivan|title=American Institute's degree 'equivalent to university's'|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160201/local/american-institutes-degree-equivalent-to-universitys.600851|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=1 February 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201174356/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160201/local/american-institutes-degree-equivalent-to-universitys.600851|archivedate=1 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nHowever, on 11 March 2016, Sadeen Education Investment Ltd was notified by a judicial letter that licensed higher education institutions are prohibited from using the word \"university\" in their advertising and publicity, unless they have been granted that status formally.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vella|first1=Matthew|title=Watchdog fines Sadeen for marketing unlicensed 'university'|url=http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/63682/watchdog_fines_sadeen_over_aum_logo|work=Malta Today|date=3 April 2016}}</ref> On 6 May 2016, Economy Minister [[Christian Cardona]] said that he had \"no doubt that this will be a University and not an institute. This is part of a process, but the project will result in a University\".<ref name=\"Times0516\">{{cite news|last1=Martin|first1=Ivan|title=American Institute courses could start this year|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160506/local/american-institute-courses-could-start-this-year.611196|work=timesofmalta.com|date=6 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe National Commission for Further and Higher Education (NCFHE) officially accredited the AUM on 30 June 2016, after a 14-month process which included financial and academic evaluations. The commission imposed a number of conditions on the AUM, including an annual audit by the [[Clemson University]].<ref>{{cite news|title=American University of Malta gets accreditation at last|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160630/local/american-university-of-malta-gets-accreditation-at-last.617262|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=30 June 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701130607/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160630/local/american-university-of-malta-gets-accreditation-at-last.617262|archivedate=1 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Sansone|first1=Kurt|title=Conditions imposed on Sadeen Group for university licence 'are not negotiable'|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160703/local/conditions-imposed-on-sadeen-group-for-university-licence-are-not.617495|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=3 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703105715/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160703/local/conditions-imposed-on-sadeen-group-for-university-licence-are-not.617495|archivedate=3 July 2016}}</ref> Sadeen asked for a compromise on these conditions, but the commission insisted that they were not negotiable.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sansone|first1=Kurt|title=No university licence for Sadeen, one month before 'first student intake'|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160910/local/no-university-licence-for-sadeen-one-month-before-first-student-intake.624564|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=10 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910171108/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160910/local/no-university-licence-for-sadeen-one-month-before-first-student-intake.624564|archivedate=10 September 2016}}</ref> After the conditions were accepted, the commission issued a 5-year university licence on 16 September 2016.<ref name=\"ourbeginnings\">{{cite web|title=Our Beginnings|url=http://aum.edu.mt/en/article/5/Our-Beginnings|website=American University of Malta|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106002945/http://aum.edu.mt/en/article/5/Our-Beginnings|archivedate=6 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sadeen granted 5-year licence to run American University of Malta|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160919/local/sadeen-granted-5-year-licence-to-run-american-university-of-malta.625569|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=19 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920185425/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160919/local/sadeen-granted-5-year-licence-to-run-american-university-of-malta.625569|archivedate=20 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nTwo former employees of the National Commission for Further and Higher Education, both directly involved in the accreditation of the AUM, were hired by the university as lecturers in August 2019.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=American University of Malta Hires Two Lecturers from Its Own Education Regulator|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/american-university-of-malta-hires-two-lecturers-from-its-own-education-regulator/|work=Lovin Malta|date=13 August 2019}}</ref> One of the two former NCFHE employees hired by the AUM visited the campus for an inspection soon after the mass firing of faculty in January 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=Interview: The Man who came from Baku (3)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/08/interview-the-man-who-came-in-from-baku-3/|website=manueldelia.com|date=19 August 2019}}</ref> This episode became known as the accreditation-for-jobs scandal. Despite suspicions of ethical impropriety, an inquiry was never conducted.\n\n===Troubled tenure of founding provost===\nIn July 2019, Provost John Ryder announced his resignation, stating that he had fulfilled his contract with the AUM but would have \"loved not to have had some of the problems or [made some of the] mistakes\" he did.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=American University Of Malta\u2019s Head John Ryder Will Retire This Month|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/american-university-of-maltas-head-john-ryder-will-retire-this-month/|work=Lovin Malta|date=12 July 2019}}</ref> These mistakes included hiring too many faculty for the 2017-18 academic year, firing those same faculty en masse in January 2018, consistently hiding student enrolment figures to avoid media scrutiny and enacting poor quality assurance processes, resulting in the hiring of faculty who were guilty of academic plagiarism and degree fraud. Ryder was promptly replaced by another American higher education administrator, Jeremy Brown. \n\nRyder's decision to hire too many faculty before the first academic term and fire them without cause at the start of the second term damaged the institution's international reputation and complicated efforts to make cooperative agreements with other universities, even after his departure. [[Arkansas State University]] reconsidered its earlier decision to collaborate with the AUM on dual degree programs after uncovering former employees' negative comments on the site [[Glassdoor]] describing the mass termination event.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ivan|title=Concerns halt partnership between AUM and US university|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/concerns-halt-partnership-between-aum-and-us-university.733312|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=5 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=American University of Malta Company Reviews|url=https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/American-University-of-Malta-Reviews-E2075737.htm|work=[[Glassdoor]]|date=12 September 2019}}</ref> In an interview with investigative journalist Lizzie Eldridge, Ryder confessed that although he was not among the faculty fired in January 2018, it was still the \"worst day of my professional life by far.\"<ref>{{cite blog|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=Interview: The Man who came from Baku (3)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/08/interview-the-man-who-came-in-from-baku-3/|work=Truth be Told|date=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Criticisms==\nMembers of the Maltese political elite, media, civil society, academe and the diplomatic community have all raised critical questions about the university. Former AUM employees have also expressed concerns about the fledgling higher education institution.\n\n===Not American===\nOne criticism is that the AUM is not authentically American. The company behind the project is from Jordan, not the United States. Almost a year before her death, Maltese journalist [[Daphne Caruana Galizia]] noted that \"the man the Jordanian outfit has chosen to be rector of this questionable 'university' is John Ryder, who is the only American aspect of the project\" <ref>{{cite web|title=From Baku to the 'American University of Malta'|url=https://daphnecaruanagalizia.com/2016/09/baku-american-university-malta/|website=daphnecaruanagalizia.com|date=September 25, 2016}}</ref> In 2018, the AUM hired an American president, Lewis N. Walker, as well.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Attard|first1=Rachel|title=Plans on Zonqor will only start when Dock 1 campus nears full capacity \u2013 new AUM president|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2018-02-25/local-news/Plans-on-Zonqor-will-only-start-when-Dock-1-campus-nears-full-capacity-new-AUM-president-6736185288|work=Malta Independent|date=February 25, 2018}}</ref>   \n\nIn a series of articles on the AUM, titled 'When is a University not a University?,' investigative journalist Lizzie Eldridge suggested that one possible explanation for why the AUM retains its American identity is to \"maintain appearances\" as a legitimate higher education enterprise: \"Sometimes, as, for example, in instances of money laundering, where a company is deliberately set up as a front, appearances are crucial.\" <ref>{{cite blog|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=When is a university not a university? (3)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/06/when-is-a-university-not-a-university-3/|work=manueldelia.com|date=June 6, 2019}}</ref> Rumours that the AUM selectively recruited U.S. citizens to make the institution appear American are substantiated by an ex-staff member who claimed that in a Skype interview with provost John Ryder, he was told that \u2018the main thing you have going for you is that you\u2019re American.\u2019 <ref>{{cite blog|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=When is a university not a university? (1)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/06/when-is-a-university-not-a-university-1/|website=manueldelia.com|date=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nPhilip G. Altbach, Boston College faculty member and director of the Center for International Higher Education, expressed concern that institutions such as Sadeen-owned AUM are \"business interests starting universities to make money using the American brand.\" <ref>{{cite news|last1=Jaschik|first1=Scott|title=Is Newest 'American U. of...' Really American?|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/05/11/questions-raised-about-whether-american-u-malta-really-american|work=[[Inside Higher Ed]]|date=May 11, 2015}}</ref> \n\nWhen asked in an interview about her views concerning the controversial American university in Malta, outgoing U.S. Ambassador to Malta [[G. Kathleen Hill]] insisted \"It's not American...it's not an American initiative but an initiative by the Sadeen Group which is out of Jordan.\" <ref>{{cite interview|title='The United States is more than President Trump'|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20180930/interview/the-united-states-is-more-than-president-trump.690344|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=September 30, 2018}}</ref> \n\nTo this criticism, the AUM's provost John Ryder responded that the university is \"not a brand or offshoot, or run by any American university ... [but it is] American in curriculum and organisation.\"<ref name=\"times2016-09-25\">{{cite news|last1=Sansone|first1=Kurt|title=AUM owner aspires for 'higher education diamond in the Mediterranean'|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160925/local/diamond-waiting-to-shine.625996|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=25 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160926161256/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160925/local/diamond-waiting-to-shine.625996|archivedate=26 September 2016}}</ref> The curricula are officially provided by DePaul University, Chicago. A spokesperson for DePaul University issued a statement, qualifying the legitimacy of AUM's curricula: \"Faculty designed degree programs in areas that were requested, with the dual goals of being academically well-designed and meeting regulatory requirements in Malta. Individual faculty members were selected with the help of teams -- composed of associate deans, school directors and department chairs -- in the relevant colleges. Faculty then were asked to design the curriculum, and they were compensated for their work,\" also adding; \"[t]he right to use our name (DePaul University) is specifically in connection to the curriculum. While specifics of any DePaul contract are proprietary, I can tell you that it went through the usual, internal multi-step review process.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jaschik|first1=Scott|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/05/11/questions-raised-about-whether-american-u-malta-really-american|title=Questions raised about whether American U. of Malta is really American|work=[[Inside Higher Ed]]|date= 11 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Lack of transparency and violation of public trust===\nCriticism has also been levelled at the AUM and Maltese Labour government for keeping the contents of its agreements secret from the Maltese public. Maltese Prime Minister Joseph Muscat was accused of a lack of transparency with regard to how government agreements with Sadeen were made.  He responded by saying that the public was informed on the first occasion.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u2018I can\u2019t see how I can be more transparent\u2019|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150517/interview/i-cant-see-how-i-can-be-more-transparent.568415|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=17 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220212411/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150517/interview/i-cant-see-how-i-can-be-more-transparent.568415|archivedate=20 December 2015}}</ref> NGOs have called for the publication of the agreement between the government and Sadeen Group.<ref>{{cite news|title=NGOs urge publication of Sadeen deal for university|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20151103/local/ngos-urge-publication-of-sadeen-deal-for-university.590697|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=3 November 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220214744/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20151103/local/ngos-urge-publication-of-sadeen-deal-for-university.590697|archivedate=20 December 2015}}</ref> A pressing concern is that without full transparency, the government's agreed-upon terms could serve the interests of Sadeen, while costing the Maltese taxpayer and undermining public trust.\n\nFormer AUM employees have criticized the AUM for its lack of transparency. A former staff member has called the AUM's social media and marketing campaigns \"smoke and mirrors,\" meant to hide the \"AUM\u2019s activities...from the public eye, behind a Facebook page designed to make you believe you\u2019ve entered an idyllic higher education wonderland, in which it\u2019s nearly impossible to distinguish between fiction and fact, fantasy and reality, glitz and horror.\" <ref>{{cite web|title='Smoke and mirrors: The personal account of an AUM staff member'|url=https://theshiftnews.com/2019/03/02/smoke-and-mirrors-the-personal-account-of-an-aum-staff-member/|work=The Shift News|date=28 February 2019}}</ref> A former lecturer at the AUM cited a confidentiality clause in the institution's standard employment contract that restricts transparency by threatening punitive measures against employees who leak information to the media. The lecturer reports: \"There was a confidentiality clause which stated that we would have to pay back twice our yearly salary, if we broke it\u2014a provision that is quite bizarre in America, and unheard of in Malta.\" <ref>{{cite web|title='Promise and Betrayal: Former American University of Malta Lecturer Speaks Out'|url=http://www.islesoftheleft.org/promise-betrayal-a-former-american-university-of-malta-lecturer-speaks-out|work=Isles of the Left|date=31 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, the AUM's plans to develop protected land in Zonqor, which were previously a  matter of public record, disappeared from the Malta Planning Authority website. This event coincided with the Planning Authority's adoption of a new policy to only disclose documents which are part of completed development applications. So long as the AUM maintains an incomplete application, it can effectively hide from public view the planning documents for the controversial second campus at Zonqor Point. The Planning Authority's policy has since come under scrutiny by the Ombudsman. <ref>{{cite news|title=\u2018Ombudsman asked to investigate restriction on information on planning website\u2019|url=|work=[[Malta_Today]]|date=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Locating university in higher education saturated Malta===\nThe Maltese government has also been criticized for permitting AUM, a foreign university, to establish itself in the small country of Malta, which is already home to several higher education institutions.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mayo|first1=Peter|title=Of Universities, Monopolies, and Public Goods|journal=Think|url=http://www.um.edu.mt/think/of-universities-monopolies-and-public-goods/|publisher=[[University of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220183841/http://www.um.edu.mt/think/of-universities-monopolies-and-public-goods/|archivedate=20 December 2015}}</ref> The government stated that the AUM would end the monopoly that the [[University of Malta]] has on higher education.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lindsay|first1=David|title=Government seeking to end University of Malta\u2019s \u2018monopoly\u2019|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2015-05-03/local-news/Government-seeking-to-end-University-of-Malta-s-monopoly-6736134834|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=3 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150807015710/http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2015-05-03/local-news/Government-seeking-to-end-University-of-Malta-s-monopoly-6736134834|archivedate=7 August 2015}}</ref> In response to this, lecturers at the University of Malta disagreed with the use of the term \"monopoly\", stating that the university already competes with other institutions such as [[MCAST]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Lecturers rubbish PM's claim of university monopoly|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150520/local/lecturers-rubbish-pms-claim-of-university-monopoly.568972|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=20 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150522183824/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150520/local/lecturers-rubbish-pms-claim-of-university-monopoly.568972|archivedate=22 May 2015}}</ref> The Maltese Ministry of Education has supported other foreign higher education start-ups in Malta, for instance, Global College and Woolf University.<ref>{{cite web|title=\nStudy World Global College Malta|url=http://www.swehg.com/swgcm/|date=2016}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=\nOxford researcher seeks Malta accreditation for world\u2019s first \u2018Blockchain University\u2019|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/oxford-researcher-seeks-malta-accreditation-for-worlds-first-blockchain-university/|work=Lovin Malta|date=27 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Faculty recruitment for accreditation purposes only===\nMaltese blogger and political commentator Manuel Delia and a dismissed AUM lecturer criticised the Maltese accreditor and the AUM, alleging that the initial recruitment of faculty, including several highly qualified academics from the United States and Britain, \"was a scam to demonstrate academic prowess to the National Council for Further and Higher Education in order to acquire accreditation.\" <ref>{{cite web|last1=Delia|first1=Manuel|title=Martin Scicluna's commission duped by AUM\u2014former lecturer|url=https://manueldelia.com/2018/06/martin-sciclunas-commission-duped-by-aum-former-lecturer/|website=manueldelia.com|date=1 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Promise and Betrayal: Former American University of Malta Lecturer Speaks Out|url=http://www.islesoftheleft.org/promise-betrayal-a-former-american-university-of-malta-lecturer-speaks-out|work=Isles of the Left|date=31 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=AUM Spotlight|url=https://twitter.com/AUM_Spotlight|website=twitter.com|date=3 June 2018}}</ref> In the aftermath of the mass firing event in January 2018, new faculty demonstrated reduced qualifications, received significantly lower salaries and, in at least four cases, were guilty of ethical improprieties of which their predecessors were not.<ref>{{cite news|title=Disgraced lecturer forced to leave AUM after reports of plagiarism|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20180203/local/disgraced-lecturer-forced-to-leave-aum-after-reports-of-plagiarism.669611|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=3 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=American University of Malta Lecturer Suspected of Lying About His Oxford PhD|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/news-breaking/breaking-american-university-of-malta-lecturer-suspected-of-lying-about-his-oxford-phd|work=Lovin Malta|date=12 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=American University of Malta Hires Two Lecturers from Its Own Education Regulator|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/american-university-of-malta-hires-two-lecturers-from-its-own-education-regulator/|work=Lovin Malta|date=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Negative impact on cultural heritage, quality of life and public space===\nDespite government projections that the AUM project would improve the social and economic situation of southern Malta, Media coverage points to the university's negative impact on the local Bormla community and the greater Three Cities region. Reports indicate declining quality of life and reduced public access to open space and cultural heritage sites. \n\nExpressing a concern \"to safeguard the public interest\" by preserving open spaces and historical sites, the Partit Demokratiku opposed the university's application filed with planning authorities to expand the Dock 1 campus into the nearby Cottonera district, including a student dormitory, underground parking garage and a rooftop pool.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2019-03-23/local-news/PD-to-safeguard-public-interest-in-relation-to-AUM-extension-6736205530|title=PD 'to safeguard public interest' in relation to AUM extension|work=Malta Independent|date=23 March 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn March 2019, Maltese environmental NGO Flimkien g\u0127al Ambjent A\u0127jar warned that the planned extension of the AUM campus would effectively privatise the majority of public space along the Bormla waterfront and destroy cultural landmarks. \"Such a building in this historically and visually sensitive area should be restored and rehabilitated through best practice and not simply bulldozed to make way for incompatible uses to the detriment of cultural heritage.\" <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20190328/local/planned-aum-extension-will-have-direct-detrimental-impact-on-cottonera.705806|title=Planned AUM extension will have 'direct detrimental impact' on Cottonera, FAA warns|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=28 March 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn September 2019, citizens in the Three Cities region formed the civil action group ''Azzjoni: Tuna Artna Lura'' (Maltese for ''Action: Give Us Back Our Land'') and started a petition to oppose the AUM's planned construction of a dormitory between the British and Knights Buildings, which would deprive the community of public space and a heritage site.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/cottonera-residents-form-action-group-to-oppose-aum-dorm-plans.732850|title=American University Malta's extension plans opposed by residents, PN|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=3 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2019-09-03/local-news/Civil-action-group-urges-people-to-sign-petition-against-AUM-expansion-6736213036|title=Civil action group urges people to sign petition against AUM expansion|work=Malta Independent|date=3 September 2019}}</ref> In a protest video, activists demonstrated the graphic damage the AUM's expansion would inflict upon the heritage site, superimposing the planned buildings on top of iconic European landmarks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/watch-cottonera-activists-use-paris-and-rome-to-make-their-point.749299|title=Watch: Cottonera activists use Paris and Rome to make their point|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=12 November 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn 19 November 2019, the Environmental Commission of the Catholic Church in Malta (Curia) publicly declared its opposition to the AUM extension, citing its deleterious effects on Cottonera resident wellbeing and heritage protection: \u201cThe application to occupy some of the few remaining open spaces in the heart of Cottonera, in order to accommodate facilities for AUM, is a clear example of these dangers [to quality of life and heritage preservation]. When so many doubts have been expressed about the need or even the usefulness of these facilities, and when they are evidently not in the best interest of the people of Cottonera, one cannot but be gravely concerned about who is being served by planning in this country.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|last1=Costa|first1=Massimo|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/98738/aum_extension_threatens_residents_wellbeing_and_areas_historical_heritage_curia_warns#.XdbQKVdKjIU|title=AUM extension threatens residents' wellbeing and area's historical heritage, Curia warns|work=[[Malta Today]]|date=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn response to pressure from activists and political leaders, the Maltese Planning Authority rejected the AUM's proposed extension to the campus on the Dock 1 site, citing the need to preserve cultural heritage, maintain public open space and ensure the continued view of the Gates of Fort St. Michael from Bormla, which would have been blocked by the planned building.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Debono|first1=James|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/environment/townscapes/97671/planning_authority_american_university_extension_decision#.XY6bl25uLIV|title=Planning Authority to reject American University extension|work=[[Malta Today]]|date=26 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Inadequate quality assurance===\nThe AUM has also been criticised for its poor quality assurance practices. Currently the AUM is accredited by the Maltese National Commission for Further and Higher Education, but has not been able to meet the more rigorous standards of U.S. accreditation.<ref>{{cite news|title=American University of Malta gets accreditation at last|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160630/local/american-university-of-malta-gets-accreditation-at-last.617262|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=30 June 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701130607/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160630/local/american-university-of-malta-gets-accreditation-at-last.617262|archivedate=1 July 2016}}</ref> \n\nIn at least two instances, Provost John Ryder and Quality Assurance Manager Rania Allam failed to meet minimum quality assurance standards for recruitment and hiring. Soon after the mass firing of faculty in January 2018, the AUM recruited, hired and employed a lecturer with a history of committing plagiarism, clearly having violated the principle of academic integrity.<ref>{{cite news|title=Disgraced lecturer forced to leave AUM after reports of plagiarism|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20180203/local/disgraced-lecturer-forced-to-leave-aum-after-reports-of-plagiarism.669611|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=3 February 2018}}</ref> Due to inadequate quality assurance, Ryder and Allam allowed a second faculty member, fraudulently claiming to hold academic credentials he did not, to join the AUM faculty.<ref>{{cite news|title=American University of Malta Lecturer Suspected of Lying About His Oxford PhD|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/news-breaking/breaking-american-university-of-malta-lecturer-suspected-of-lying-about-his-oxford-phd|work=Lovin Malta|date=12 February 2018}}</ref> \n\nInvestigative journalist Lizzie Eldridge has noted how the AUM's mass dismissal of faculty combined with poor quality assurance in hiring replacement faculty normalises unethical practices for new enterprises in Malta: \"It becomes normal for a \u2018start-up\u2019 university to engage in mass firings of their newly employed and highly qualified staff and then hire both a plagiarist and a fraud.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=Guest Series: Pandora's Box (3)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/09/guest-series-pandoras-box-3/|website=manueldelia.com|date=29 September 2019}}</ref>     \n\nIn August 2019, two former employees of the Maltese National Commission for Further and Higher Education, both directly involved in the AUM's accreditation process, were hired by the university as lecturers, suggesting the possibility of a revolving door or quid pro quo arrangement between the accreditor and the AUM.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=American University of Malta Hires Two Lecturers from Its Own Education Regulator|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/american-university-of-malta-hires-two-lecturers-from-its-own-education-regulator/|work=Lovin Malta|date=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=Interview: The Man who came from Baku (3)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/08/interview-the-man-who-came-in-from-baku-3/|website=manueldelia.com|date=19 August 2019}}</ref> \n\nUniversity of Malta Education Professor and public intellectual Peter Mayo described the difficulty of obtaining US accreditation with poor quality assurance practices as the AUM's primary obstacle to becoming a legitimate higher education institution: \"The main struggle for institutions such as the new AUM, situated on an island at the heart of the Mediterranean, strategically posed [sic] to attract students from North Africa and Europe, is, not only to attract an adequate number of students (this has been incredibly low to the extent that some recruited academics were dismissed before the end of their probation period), but, one would imagine, to establish links with US universities and perhaps seek accreditation from important USA agencies.\" <ref>{{cite news|last1=Mayo|first1=Peter|title=US Higher Education Influence Takes a Different Turn|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2019/03/22/110244/|work=[[CounterPunch]]|date=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe AUM has still not been able to obtain U.S. accreditation.\n\n==Controversies==\nIn the first three years of the AUM's existence, the higher education institution has been plagued by a number of controversies.  Despite the university's small student body, high employee turnover and growing legal troubles, Malta's Education Minister [[Evarist Bartolo]] insisted that the AUM is not entirely a  \u201cgarage operation\u201d <ref>{{cite news|last1=Grech|first1=Helena|title=Minister would rather see the American University of Malta 'start small, grow gradually'|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2017-11-13/local-news/Education-Minister-would-rather-see-AUM-start-small-grow-gradually-6736181366|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=13 November 2017}}</ref> \n\n===Suspicions of corruption, kickbacks and quid pro quo===\nIn 2019, Maltese Prime Minister Joseph Muscat, who had persuaded Hani Saleh to locate the university in Malta, was named by the [[Organized Crime and Corruption Reporting Project]] (OCCRP) as 'man of the year in organised crime and corruption'.<ref>{{cite news |title=Joseph Muscat named \u20182019 man of the year in organised crime and corruption\u2019 |url=https://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2019-12-27/local-news/Joseph-Muscat-named-2019-man-of-the-year-in-organised-crime-and-corruption-6736217841 |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=The Malta Independent |date=December 27, 2019}}</ref> In 2020, immediately prior to the ascension of Muscat's successor, [[Robert Abela]], it was discovered that \u20ac20,000 airline tickets to Dubai, used by Muscat, his wife and children for a recent family vacation, were purchased in Jordan, provoking suspicion that they constituted a kickback from Sadeen Group for the AUM concessions.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Muscat|first1=Caroline|url=https://theshiftnews.com/2020/01/07/tickets-to-dubai-for-joseph-muscats-family-were-purchased-in-jordan/|title=Tickets to Dubai for Joseph Muscat\u2019s family were purchased in Jordan|work=The Shift News|date=7 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe Maltese press also raised concerns that the National Commission for Further and Higher Education (NCFHE) turned a blind eye to the mass dismissal of faculty in January 2018 in a quid pro quo arrangement with the AUM. Two former employees of the NCFHE, both directly involved in the AUM's accreditation, were hired as lecturers by the university in August 2019, less than two years after the dismissal of the university's entire faculty: \"Manuel Vella Rago was until recently Head of Quality Assurance at NCFHE, while Audrey Abela was its Head of Accreditation, both key roles in the regulation of the AUM.\" <ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=American University of Malta Hires Two Lecturers from Its Own Education Regulator|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/american-university-of-malta-hires-two-lecturers-from-its-own-education-regulator/|work=Lovin Malta|date=13 August 2019}}</ref> According to investigative journalist Lizzie Eldridge, \"Manuel Vella Rago\u2019s previous position [was not only] as Head of Quality Assurance at the NCFHE,  . . . he was [also] one of the inspectors who made that \u2018surprise visit\u2019 to the AUM last year [soon after the mass firing of the AUM's faculty in January 2018].\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=Interview: The Man who came from Baku (3)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/08/interview-the-man-who-came-in-from-baku-3/|website=manueldelia.com|date=19 August 2019}}</ref> In spite of these revelations, no investigation of the accreditation-for-jobs scandal was ever initiated.\n\n===Low student enrolments and inability to achieve targets===\nIn the AUM's first two years, refusals by then-Provost John Ryder to publicly release the official enrollment figures was a recurring flashpoint of controversy. An early promotional video presented the new university's plan to admit 1,000 students in its first year, eventually reaching a total enrollment of 4,000 students by its fourth year.<ref>{{YouTube|id=Y01mF8p13tk|title=AUM Promo Video}}</ref> \n\nThe AUM officially began offering classes on Tuesday September 12, 2017, rather than Monday September 11, to avoid association with the [[September 11 attacks]] anniversary.<ref name=\"maltachamber\">{{cite news|title=AUM Opens its Doors to the First Batch of Students|url=http://www.maltachamber.org.mt/page.aspx?rid=8697&preview=1&c=95493AB4B36E9D8D6637317593DB929F7C5700C8&k=-534249962|work=maltachamber.org.mt|date=12 September 2017}}</ref> Asked how many students the AUM admitted for the Fall semester (academic year 2017-18), then-Provost Ryder would only say that student recruitment was \u201cproving to be challenging.\" <ref>{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ivan|title=AUM student enrolment is 'proving challenging', provost says|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20170906/local/aum-student-enrolment-is-proving-challenging-provost-says.657269|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=6 September 2017}}</ref> In November of the same year, the [[Times of Malta]] reported that the AUM's revised plan was to enroll 330 students in its first semester, but the \"university managed to attract 15 students.\"<ref name=\"timesofmalta1\">{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ivan|title=AUM firing staff after failing to attract students|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20171112/local/aum-firing-staff-after-failing-to-attract-students.662834|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=12 November 2017}}</ref> The figure was denied by university officials.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schembri Orland|first1=Kevin|title=AUM says it has more than 15 students, but still doesn't divulge number|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2017-11-19/local-news/AUM-says-it-has-more-than-15-students-but-still-doesn-t-divulge-number-6736181619|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=19 November 2017}}</ref> Four days later, Ryder acknowledged in a [[Television Malta]] interview that the AUM student body numbered 23.<ref>{{cite news|title=AUM rector says original targets were not realistic but is confident for the future|url=https://www.tvm.com.mt/en/news/aum-rector-says-original-targets-were-not-realistic-but-is-confident-for-the-future/|work=[[Television Malta]]|date=24 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt the start of the subsequent academic year (2018\u201319), the AUM's provost and the director of student recruitment only disclosed the number of countries from which it received applications, but not the total numbers of applicants or enrolments.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sansone|first1=Kurt|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/89051/aum_will_not_divulge_number_of_new_students_yet#.XDHRzUxFzmI|title=American University of Malta will not divulge number of new students yet|work=MaltaToday|date=27 August 2018}}</ref> Despite then-Provost Ryder's promises to eventually share enrolment figures with the media, none were ever officially released. An anonymous source at the university divulged to the [[Times of Malta]] that six new students had been admitted in the fledgling institution's second year of operations.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ivan|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20180916/local/only-six-new-students-enrolled-at-aum-so-far.689221|title=Only six new students enrolled at AUM so far|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=16 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn his role as Chairman of the Cottonera Rehabilitation Committee, Maltese Parliament Member and Labour Party insider [[Glenn Bedingfield]] expressed scepticism that the AUM would fulfil its contractual obligation with the Government of Malta to reach the agreed-upon number of students four years after the building phase of the Cospicua campus is completed: \"I am beginning to doubt whether they [the AUM] will ever be able to attract the 4,000 students in the promised timeframe [2025 to 2029].\" <ref>{{cite news|last1=Bedingfield|first1=Glenn|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/aum-give-us-back-our-land-glenn-bedingfield.729326|title=AUM: Give us back our land|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=18 August 2019}}</ref> On the 13 October 2019, the [[Times of Malta]] reported that the AUM had only recruited one-fifth of the targeted number of students, 143 of the 710 it had promised the Maltese government.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Micallef|first1=Keith|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/aum-student-population-fifth-of-promised-number.746091|title=AUM student population is a fifth of promised number|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Mass dismissals and other personnel decisions===\nAUM personnel decisions have also generated controversy, raising concerns about the legality of the new institution's employment policies and practices. Within a period of seven months, the employment contracts of 10 university employees were terminated, either by [[dismissal (employment)|dismissal]] or resignation: (1) Deputy (Construction Project) Manager (dismissal), (2) Admissions Director (dismissal), (3) Marketing and Public Relations Director (dismissal), (4) Vice President for Administrative Affairs (dismissal), (5) IT Technician (dismissal), (6) Webmaster (resignation), (7) Admissions Counselor (resignation), (8) Human Resources Director (dismissal), (9) Professor of Finance (dismissal) and (10) Dean of Student Affairs (resignation).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=This is What the American University of Malta Looks Like Two Years Later|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/news-breaking/this-is-what-the-american-university-of-malta-looks-like-two-years-later|work=lovinmalta.com|date=11 November 2017}}</ref> \n\nSeveral of these terminations precipitated legal action by ex-employees against the university. The dismissed deputy manager filed a judicial protest against Sadeen Education.<ref>{{cite news|title=American University of Malta deputy manager says claims against him were fabricated|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20170523/local/american-university-deputy-manager-says-claims-against-him-were.648810|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=23 May 2017}}</ref> The former admissions director sued the university for unfair dismissal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Couple file judicial protest claiming unfair dismissal by Sadeen Education Investment Ltd|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2017-10-20/local-news/Couple-file-judicial-protest-claiming-unfair-dismissal-by-Sadeen-Education-Investment-Ltd-6736180457|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=20 October 2017}}</ref> In a judicial protest, the former Assistant Director of Admissions alleged that the AUM fraudulently misrepresented salaries to prospective hires (wage agreed to in Euros but remunerated in U.S. Dollars), mismanaged the student recruitment process and, upon completion of the employees' service, failed to pay final salaries in full, \"presumably from loss of currency exchange.\" <ref>{{cite news|title=In judicial protest, former assistant director at AUM claims breach of contract|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2018-02-21/local-news/In-judicial-protest-former-assistant-director-at-AUM-claims-breach-of-contract-6736185146|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=21 February 2018}}</ref>   \n\nOn 4 January 2018, Provost John Ryder informed the 12 remaining AUM faculty members by e-mail that their employment with the university had been terminated without cause.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=BREAKING: American University of Malta Has Sacked All Its Faculty|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/news-breaking/breaking-american-university-of-malta-has-sacked-all-its-faculty|work=lovinmalta.com|date=4 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=AUM full time lecturers said to have been 'dismissed by email'|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2018-01-04/local-news/AUM-full-time-lectures-said-to-have-been-dismissed-by-email-6736183231|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=4 January 2018}}</ref> Five of the terminated faculty members sued the AUM for unfair dismissal and abuse of the six-month probationary period rule.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=Sued! Fresh Hell For American University of Malta as Five Sacked Lecturers Spill the Beans|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/sued-fresh-hell-for-american-university-of-malta-as-five-sacked-lecturers-spill-the-beans|work=lovinmalta.com|date=1 May 2018}}</ref> According to Maltese [[Labour law]], the six-month probationary rule stipulates that \"[t]he first six months of any employment under a contract of service is deemed to be probationary employment, unless otherwise agreed by both parties for a shorter probation period. [...] During the probationary period, either party may terminate the employment at will without reason. Provided that a week\u2019s notice of the termination of employment has to be given to the other party in the case of an employee who has been in the employment of the same employer continuously for more than one month.\" <ref>{{cite web|title=Malta Labour Law|url=http://www.fbsmalta.com/malta-labour-law/|website=www.fbsmalta.com|date=1 January 2012}}</ref> The five lecturers reached an agreement with Sadeen to settle the case before it reached adjudication, the terms of which were never made public. Arkansas State University, which signed an agreement with the AUM in March 2019 to offer dual degree programs, decided in September 2019 to freeze and scrutinize the AUM agreement after discovery of the mass firing of faculty in January 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sansone|first1=Kurt|title=AUM signs collaborative agreement with Arkansas State University|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/business/business_news/93784/aum_signs_collaborative_agreement_with_arkansas_state_university#.XW5P4PZuLIU|work=maltatoday.com.mt|date=22 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Watson|first1=Gordon|title=AUM deal with Arkansas State University frozen after nearly all staff dismissed|url=https://www.newsbook.com.mt/artikli/2019/09/02/aum-deal-with-arkansas-state-university-frozen-after-nearly-all-staff-dismissed/?lang=en|work=newsbook.com.mt|date=2 September 2019}}</ref>  \n\nIn a two hour interview with investigative journalist Lizzie Eldridge, soon-to-be-retired Provost John Ryder admitted that the mistake that led to the mass dismissal of faculty from the AUM in January 2018 was his own, an error in forecasting the number of students, courses and instructors required for the first academic year: \"Part of the problem was that we were way overstaffed because I had hired with certain assumptions about the number of students and we weren\u2019t even in the neighbourhood for the first intake of students . . . It turned out to be much more difficult than we thought. We were way over-optimistic about recruiting and hiring.\" <ref>{{cite blog|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=Interview: The Man who came from Baku (3)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/08/interview-the-man-who-came-in-from-baku-3/|work=Truth be Told|date=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, despite a significant shortfall in projected enrolments and the fresh memory of the 2018 mass firing of faculty, the institution tweeted: \"We are proud to have grown our student numbers over the years and we are even more proud that we still cultivate strong relationships between students and professors.\" <ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/aumalta?lang=en |website=American University of Malta |publisher=Twitter |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n===Legal and ethical wrongdoing by board of trustees members===\nAnother source  of controversy is the alleged legal and ethical wrongdoing by members of the AUM's board of trustees. The board members are (1) [[Prince Jean of Luxembourg]] (chair), (2) [[John Ryder (scholar)]], (3) Taddeo Scerri (chairman of the board at the [[Bank of Valletta]]), (4) Hani Salah (Chief Executive Officer of Sadeen Group), (5) [[Taher al-Masri]], (6) [[Derrick Gosselin]] and (7) Carine Boonen.<ref name=\"timesofmalta2\">{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ivan|title=American University of Malta appoints Adrian Hillman as trustee|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20171029/local/american-university-of-malta-appoints-adrian-hillman-as-trustee.661617|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=29 October 2017}}</ref> \n\nBoard member Taddeo Scerri was accused of ignoring conflicts of interest between his AUM board appointment and his current and past professional positions in Malta's financial sector.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ivan|title=No conflict of interest with American University of Malta appointment, says BOV chair|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20171103/local/no-conflict-of-interest-with-american-university-of-malta.662085|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=3 November 2017}}</ref> \n\nBoard member Derrick Gosselin exploited a so-called [[Revolving door (politics)]] between an executive position in a private energy company and a senior policy position in the Flemish government in order to unethically influence public policy for his employer's financial benefit.<ref>{{cite report|author=Greens/EFA Group in the European Parliament|title=Revolving Doors and the Fossil Fuel Industry|url=https://issuu.com/europeecologie/docs/report_of_revolving_doors_digital|page=45|date=May 2, 2018}}</ref> \n\nBoard member John Ryder, who was appointed immediately after his resignation as provost, undertook the mass firing of faculty in January 2018 as well as hiring replacement faculty with histories of plagiarism and fraud in the aftermath.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=BREAKING: American University of Malta Has Sacked All Its Faculty|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/news-breaking/breaking-american-university-of-malta-has-sacked-all-its-faculty|work=lovinmalta.com|date=4 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Disgraced lecturer forced to leave AUM after reports of plagiarism|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20180203/local/disgraced-lecturer-forced-to-leave-aum-after-reports-of-plagiarism.669611|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=3 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=American University of Malta Lecturer Suspected of Lying About His Oxford PhD|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/news-breaking/breaking-american-university-of-malta-lecturer-suspected-of-lying-about-his-oxford-phd|work=Lovin Malta|date=12 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 January 2020, Adrian Hillman, former Allied Group managing director, was removed from his role as the government's representative to the AUM board.  A spokesperson for the Maltese Ministry of Education stated, \"Mr Adrian Hillman will no longer be the Government nominee on AUM.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carabott|first1=Sarah|last2=Xuereb|first2=Matthew|title=Adrian Hillman loses gaming authority contracts, AUM board role|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/hillmans-contract-with-gaming-authority-terminated-in-zero-tolerance.765615|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=23 January 2020}}</ref> Three years prior, Hillman was appointed to the board of trustees while under criminal investigation for laundering money and receiving kickbacks from the Maltese Prime Minister's chief of staff [[Keith Schembri]], who has been implicated in the [[Panama Papers]] money laundering scheme and the assassination of investigative journalist [[Daphne Caruana Galizia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Allied Group managing director Adrian Hillman denies allegations|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160313/local/allied-group-managing-director-adrian-hillman-denies-allegations.605632|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=13 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"timesofmalta2\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Borg|first1=Jacob|last2=Grech|first2=Herman|title=Middleman's letter links Schembri and Fenech to Daphne murder|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/letter-links-schembri-and-fenech-to-daphne-murder.754435|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=2 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Difficulties with real estate company and construction contractors===\nIn the process of restoring the Dock 1 site, Sadeen has ignited controversy through its mismanagement of the construction project. After disappointingly low student enrolments, Sadeen sued a Maltese real estate company from which it purchased a hostel to serve as a student dormitory.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cocks|first1=Paul|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/90336/american_university_of_malta_tries_to_nullify_27_million_purchase_of_tarxien_hostel#.XDHJUUxFzmI|title=American University of Malta tries to nullify \u20ac2.7 million purchase of Tarxien hostel|work=Malta Today|date=23 Oct 2018}}</ref> Physical violence and threats of gun violence also ensued on the AUM campus between a contractor and subcontractor, with no intervention by campus security despite the threat posed to students, faculty and staff.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brincat|first1=Edwina|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20181203/local/contractors-come-to-blows-at-american-university-man-arraigned-after.695810|title=Contractors come to blows at American university, man arraigned after year-long search|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=3 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Poor community relations and backlash===\nDespite initial support from the local Bormla council, the AUM's continued expansion in the Dock 1 area has soured relations with some members of the Cospicua community. Citing increased traffic congestion and a shortage of vehicle parking caused by the new university's presence, Bormla's mayor requested that the university allow local residents to use 50% of the AUM's parking spaces in a planned underground complex. <ref>{{cite news|last1=Debono|first1=James|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/93722/american_university_parking_spaces_should_be_given_to_bormla_residents_mayor_says|title=American University parking spaces should be given to Borlma residents, mayor says|work=[[Malta Today]]|date=21 March 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe daughter of Malta's former prime minister Dom Mintoff, Yanna Mintoff, filed a protest with planning authorities to the proposed \"privatisation\" of public space by the AUM, warning against premature campus growth \"considering the very low uptake of the AUM educational services to date, and the lack of any positive multiplier effect on the local community and the country as a whole.\" <ref>{{cite news|last1=Debono|first1=James|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/environment/townscapes/94335/yana_mintoff_files_objection_to_american_university_expansion_in_bormla#.XLXGgPZuLmI|title=Yana Mintoff files objection to American University expansion in Bormla|work=[[Malta Today]]|date=16 April 2019}}</ref> Member of Parliament Glenn Bedingfield complained that the proposed student dormitory to be built as an extension to the Knights Building is \"too big for AUM's dozen students.\" <ref>{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Neil|url=https://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2019-08-08/local-news/Proposed-dormitory-too-big-for-AUM-s-dozen-students-MP-Gel-Bedingfield-says-6736211961|title=Proposed dormitory 'too big for AUM's dozen students,' MP Glenn Bedingfield says|work=Malta Independent|date=8 August 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn 26 September 2019, the Maltese Planning Authority board decided to reject the AUM's decision to extend the campus on the Dock 1 site, citing concerns that the building would obstruct the view of Fort St. Michael, reduce public open space and damage the social fabric of the community, thereby transforming \"Bormla into Sadeen town.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Debono|first1=James|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/environment/townscapes/97671/planning_authority_american_university_extension_decision#.XY6bl25uLIV|title=Planning Authority to reject American University extension|work=[[Malta Today]]|date=26 September 2019}}</ref> \n\nPalumbo Group, which operates the nearby dockyard, requested a court injunction to stop the AUM from blocking the parking entrance to Dock 1. \"The university cannot close off the area,\" a Palumbo representative claimed, \"as it is fundamental to the works being carried out by the dock yard.\" <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/98127/palumbo_group_and_aum_bump_heads_over_macina_parking_entrance_#.XbJDAG5FzIU|title=Palumbo Group and AUM bump heads over Macina parking entrance|work=[[Malta Today]]|date=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Speculations of a hotel development===\nThe planned extension of the Dock 1 facilities fuelled speculation that the Sadeen Group intends to declare the AUM project a failure and convert the site into a luxury hotel. A coalition of Cottonera residents and community groups \"expressed concern that the long-term objective of constructing a dormitory was to convert it to a hotel in a few years' time.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Micallef|first1=Keith|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/last-ditch-attempt-to-safeguard-skyline-from-american-university-malta.737569|title=Last ditch attempt to 'safeguard' skyline from American University Malta plans|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Students abscond to Europe===\nThe Maltese press revealed that nearly a third of the AUM's new students had absconded from Malta to mainland Europe, rather than remain in Malta to start their studies. \"In what may be a case of irregular migration,\" wrote Ivan Camilleri, Times of Malta journalist reporting on four Bangladeshi students who escaped to continental Europe, \"they are suspected to have used the Schengen visas they were granted on the strength of their student status to make their way to another EU country. The Schengen visa allows its holder free movement in 22 EU Member States and four other European countries.\" <ref>{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ivan|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/american-university-students-disappear-before-reaching-campus.670306|title=Four American University students \u2018disappear\u2019 before reaching campus|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=11 February 2018}}</ref> In an interview with investigative journalist Lizzie Eldridge, Provost John Ryder admitted that foreign students had used the AUM as a launch board into Europe. Responding defensively, he acknowledged that the absconding students posed security risks (human trafficking and terrorism), but insisted that all were reported to Maltese immigration authorities.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=Interview: The Man who came from Baku (2)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/08/interview-the-man-who-came-in-from-baku-2/|website=manueldelia.com|date=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.aum.edu.mt/#Home Official website]\n\n{{Portal bar|Education|Malta|United States}}\n\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges]]\n[[Category:Universities in Malta]]\n[[Category:Cospicua]]\n[[Category:Marsaskala]]\n[[Category:Proposed buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:Controversies in Malta]]\n[[Category:Environmental controversies]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2016]]\n[[Category:2016 establishments in Malta]]\n[[Category:2015 controversies]]\n[[Category:2016 controversies]]\n[[Category:2017 controversies]]\n[[Category:2018 controversies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name              = American University of Malta\n| native_name       = <!-- SOURCE?? Universit\u00e0 Amerikana ta' Malta -->\n| native_name_lang  = mt\n| image             = Dock no. 1.jpg\n| caption           = Renovation works at the Cospicua campus in November 2016\n| former_name       = American Institute of Malta\n| type              = [[Private university|Private]]\n| established       = {{start date and age|2016|09|16|df=y}}<ref name=\"ourbeginnings\"/>\n| founder           = Sadeen Education Investment Ltd.\n| provost           = Jeremy Brown\n| students          = 143<ref>{{cite news |last1=Micallef |first1=Keith |title=AUM student population is a fifth of promised number |url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/aum-student-population-fifth-of-promised-number.746091 |work=[[Times of Malta]] |date=31 October 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191031205710/https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/aum-student-population-fifth-of-promised-number.746091 |archivedate=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n| city              = [[Cospicua]]\n| country           = [[Malta]]\n| coordinates       = {{Coord|35|52|55|N|14|31|11.2|E|display=inline, title}}\n| website           = [http://www.aum.edu.mt/ aum.edu.mt]\n| logo              = American University of Malta logo.png\n}}\n\nThe '''American University of Malta''' ('''AUM''') is a [[private university|private]], American-style [[liberal arts college]] in [[Cospicua]], [[Malta]]. The establishment of the educational institution was announced in May 2015, and the project was originally intended to regenerate the South of Malta and give said area an economic and social boost.<ref name=opm-presentation/> Since the proposal was announced, Dock 1 in Cospicua was chosen for the head campus, while extensions are being planned for other sites in Cospicua and \u017bonqor, [[Marsaskala]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Muscat|first1=Caroline|title=Mounting opposition to use of ODZ land|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150514/local/mounting-opposition-to-use-of-odz-land.568095|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=14 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220233523/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150514/local/mounting-opposition-to-use-of-odz-land.568095|archivedate=20 December 2015}}</ref> It was officially established on 16 September 2016,<ref name=\"ourbeginnings\"/> and it opened in September 2017.<ref name=\"maltachamber\"/>\n\n==Planning and Opening==\nOn 5 May 2015, the [[Jordan]]ian construction company Sadeen Group and the [[Government of Malta]] signed an agreement at [[Auberge de Castille]] for the former to set up a private educational institution called the American University of Malta (AUM). Initially the university was planned to be located in [[Spain]], but the owner of Sadeen, Hani Salah, was persuaded to establish it in Malta by then-Prime Minister of Malta [[Joseph Muscat]].\n\nThe university was intended to accommodate 4000 students, primarily from the [[Middle East]], [[North Africa]] and [[Europe]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/heads-of-agreement-for-4000-student-american-university-expected-on.566504|title=Heads of agreement for 4,000-student American university expected on Tuesday|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=2015-09-12}}</ref> However, the university has consistently failed to meet its recruitment goals.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Micallef|first1=Keith|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/aum-student-population-fifth-of-promised-number.746091|title=AUM student population is a fifth of promised number|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=30 October 2019}}</ref> By the time all campuses are complete, it is intended to have schools of business, architecture and design, engineering, arts, sciences, and information technology, each offering one or more Bachelor Degree Programs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aum.edu.mt/bachelors-degree-programs/|title=Undergraduate Degree Programs|website=aum.edu.mt|date=1 January 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe original curricula of the AUM were provided by the [[DePaul University]]. The latter claims that it did not commit financial or human resources to the AUM, and it was not involved in any discussions with the Government of Malta.<ref>{{cite news|title=DePaul University denies involvement in site selection for proposed American University of Malta|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150508/local/depaul-university-denies-involvement-in-site-selection-for-proposed.567368|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=8 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913161255/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150508/local/depaul-university-denies-involvement-in-site-selection-for-proposed.567368|archivedate=13 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Mathews|first1=Kristin Claes|title=Faculty create curricula for American University of Malta|url=http://www.depaulnewsline.com/features/faculty-create-curricula-american-university-malta|work=DePaul Newsline|date=13 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150520003229/http://www.depaulnewsline.com/features/faculty-create-curricula-american-university-malta|archivedate=20 May 2015}}</ref> However, a member of DePaul's executive administrative team, Khaled El Zayyat, became the AUM's first Vice President of Global Initiatives: \"El Zayyat previously held teaching and administrative posts at DePaul University, Chicago, and supervised dual degree graduate programmes for DePaul University in Jordan.\" <ref>{{cite blog|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=When is a university not a university? (1)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/06/when-is-a-university-not-a-university-1/|website=manueldelia.com|date=June 4, 2019}}</ref> El Zayyat initially hired and supervised IT staff at the AUM. Two months after the IT Administrator who reported to El Zayyat, David Aquilina, was dismissed, the Maltese government hired the same individual to work in an identical capacity in the Office of the Prime Minister. \n\nThe university was originally intended to create a social and economic boost to localities in the [[South Eastern Region]] of Malta, which is regarded as being less developed than the rest of the island.<ref name=opm-presentation>{{cite web|title=Investiment g\u0127an-na\u0127a t'isfel ta' Malta \u2013 American University of Malta|url=https://opm.gov.mt/en/Documents/AUM/AUM%20PRESENTATION.pdf|website=[[Government of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304213220/https://opm.gov.mt/en/Documents/AUM/AUM%20PRESENTATION.pdf|archivedate=4 March 2016|language=Maltese}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Estimation of the Contribution to the Maltese Economy of the Development and Operation of an International Higher Academic Institution: Update Based on a Project Proposal Spread Over Two Sites|url=https://opm.gov.mt/en/Documents/AUM/AUM-EIA.pdf|website=[[Government of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703110407/https://opm.gov.mt/en/Documents/AUM/AUM-EIA.pdf|archivedate=3 July 2016}}</ref> The project has an investment of over \u20ac115 million, and it was intended to create around 400<ref name=\"opm-presentation\" /> to 750 jobs.<ref name=\"MT0516\">{{cite news|url=http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/64924/american_university_of_malta_campus_to_take_three_years_to_complete#.V3jwKfl961s|title='American University of Malta' campus to take three years to complete|last1=Dalli|first1=Miriam|date=6 May 2016|work=[[Malta Today]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604130547/http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/64924/american_university_of_malta_campus_to_take_three_years_to_complete|archivedate=4 June 2016}}</ref> The project's estimated economic output was speculated to be about \u20ac48 to \u20ac85 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160921/local/sadeens-five-year-licence-dictated-by-law.625667|title=Sadeen\u2019s five-year licence 'dictated by law'|last1=Sansone|first1=Kurt|date=21 September 2016|work=[[Times of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922140626/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160921/local/sadeens-five-year-licence-dictated-by-law.625667|archivedate=22 September 2016}}</ref> As of September 2016, demand for property in Cospicua reportedly increased as a result of the university project.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bartolo|first1=Janice|title=Xhieda li l-American University of Malta bdiet tag\u0127ti spinta lin-na\u0127a t'isfel ta' Malta|url=http://www.one.com.mt/news/xhieda-li-l-american-university-of-malta-bdiet-taghti-spinta-lin-naha-tisfel-ta-malta/|work=[[One Productions|One]]|date=27 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019133208/http://www.one.com.mt/news/xhieda-li-l-american-university-of-malta-bdiet-taghti-spinta-lin-naha-tisfel-ta-malta/|archivedate=19 October 2016|language=Maltese}}</ref> Also, concerns have arisen that the university's presence threatens the heritage and quality of life in the Bormla community and Three Cities region.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Vella|first1=Matthew|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/environment/townscapes/97245/cottonera_activists_urge_residents_to_petition_against_aum_extension#.XXN4fPZuLIU|title=Cottonera activists urge residents to petition against AUM extension|work=MaltaToday|date=3 September 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/cottonera-residents-unite-against-over-development.736955|title=Cottonera residents unite against over-development|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=22 September 2019}}</ref>\n  \nThe university originally planned to take in its first students on October 2016, with lectures at [[SmartCity Malta]] until the head campus was completed.<ref name=times2015-08-20/> The beginning of the first academic year was later moved to 28 August 2017, with lectures held at the Dock No. 1 campus in Cospicua.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sansone|first1=Kurt|title=Lectures at AUM to start on August 28|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160925/local/lectures-at-aum-to-start-on-august-28.625991|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=25 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160926154655/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160925/local/lectures-at-aum-to-start-on-august-28.625991|archivedate=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, [[John Ryder (scholar)|John Ryder]] was named as the head of the American University of Malta, assuming the dual roles of Provost and Acting Vice President of the AUM. Ryder's qualifications for the post included a terminal academic degree in Philosophy and two-years' experience as president of Khazar University in Azerbaijan <ref>{{cite news|title=Former Baku university rector to head 'American Institute of Malta'|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160127/local/former-baku-university-rector-to-head-american-institute-of-malta.600270|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=26 January 2016}}</ref>     \n\n===Location of campus and use of ODZ land===\n[[File:Site for the future American Institute of Malta.jpeg|thumb|\u017bonqor Point, where part of the university campus is to be built]]\n\nWhen the university project was announced in May 2015, the government offered the Sadeen Group {{convert|90000|m2|abbr=on}} of Outside Development Zone (ODZ) land near \u017bonqor Point in [[Marsaskala]] on which to build the university. A natural park, partially funded by the university, would be set up nearby. The proposal to use ODZ land raised concerns among environmentalists, including the NGOs [[Flimkien g\u0127al Ambjent A\u0127jar]], [[Friends of the Earth (Malta)|Friends of the Earth Malta]], Ramblers Association, [[Din l-Art \u0126elwa]], NatureTrust Malta, [[Birdlife]] Malta, Malta Organic Agriculture Movement and Greenhouse. The Malta Developers Association also stated that a better site should be found,<ref name=times2015-05-05>{{cite news|title=Fort San Leonardo may be incorporated in new university campus|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150505/local/update-3-fort-san-leonardo-may-be-incorporated-in-new-university.566883|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=5 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928173056/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150505/local/update-3-fort-san-leonardo-may-be-incorporated-in-new-university.566883|archivedate=28 September 2015}}</ref> while the Church criticized the process used to select the land for the university.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Muscat|first1=Caroline|title=Church slams government\u2019s handling of university bid|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150521/local/church-slams-governments-handling-of-university-bid.569018|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=21 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220213628/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150521/local/church-slams-governments-handling-of-university-bid.569018|archivedate=20 December 2015}}</ref> Meanwhile, residents of Marsaskala and southern Malta supported the university project by signing a petition in its favour.<ref>{{cite news|title=Tan-nofsinhar ji\u0121bru petizzjoni favur il-pro\u0121ett tal-universit\u00e0|url=http://www.inewsmalta.com/dart/20150615-tan-nofsinhar-ji-bru-petizzjoni-favur-il-pro-ett-tal-universit|work=iNews Malta|date=16 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618014128/http://www.inewsmalta.com/dart/20150615-tan-nofsinhar-ji-bru-petizzjoni-favur-il-pro-ett-tal-universit|archivedate=18 June 2015|language=Maltese}}</ref> \n\nThe government initially planned to include the 19th-century [[Fort Leonardo]] within the university campus. Prime Minister Joseph Muscat also stated that constructing the university in Marsaskala would pressure the owners of the former [[Jerma Palace Hotel]] to redevelop the site, which has fallen into disrepair since being closed down in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dalli|first1=Kim|title=University plan \u2018puts pressure on Jerma site\u2019|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150506/local/university-plan-puts-pressure-on-jerma-site.566951|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=6 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150929031031/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150506/local/university-plan-puts-pressure-on-jerma-site.566951|archivedate=29 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nMuscat responded to the environmentalists' criticism by stating that the [[Malta Environment and Planning Authority]] would consider other sites as long as they are located in the southern part of the island.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Martin|first1=Ivan|title=\u2018University will generate \u20ac25m a year\u2019|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150504/local/university-will-generate-25m-a-year.566645|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=4 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220195817/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150504/local/university-will-generate-25m-a-year.566645|archivedate=20 December 2015}}</ref> A public consultation process was subsequently made in order to select an alternative site for the university campus.<ref>{{cite web|title=The American University of Malta \u2013 Preliminary Alternative Sites Evaluation Report|url=https://opm.gov.mt/en/Documents/AUM/Preliminary%20Alternative%20Sites%20Evaluation%20Report.pdf|website=[[Government of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304214404/https://opm.gov.mt/en/Documents/AUM/Preliminary%20Alternative%20Sites%20Evaluation%20Report.pdf|archivedate=4 March 2016|date=August 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 May 2015, the Front \u0126arsien ODZ ([[Maltese language|Maltese]] for ''Front for the Protection of ODZ'') was set up in response to the proposed development at \u017bonqor Point. The group aims to protect all ODZ land in Malta, and it includes then-[[Labour Party (Malta)|Labour]] MP, turned [[Democratic Party (Malta)|Democratic Party]] (PD) members, [[Marlene Farrugia]], [[Whip (politics)|government whip]] Godfrey Farrugia and former [[Alternattiva Demokratika]] politician, turned Nationalist Party (PN) member, [[Michael Briguglio]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Neil|title=Godfrey, Marlene Farrugia join 'Front Harsien ODZ,' group says Zonqor project can be stopped|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2015-05-23/local-news/Front-Harsien-ODZ-launched-not-just-against-Zonqor-university-but-all-other-ODZ-developments-6736136030|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=23 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150811133750/http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2015-05-23/local-news/Front-Harsien-ODZ-launched-not-just-against-Zonqor-university-but-all-other-ODZ-developments-6736136030|archivedate=11 August 2015}}</ref> On 20 June, the front held a protest in [[Valletta]] against the development, and it was attended by 3000 people.<ref>{{cite news|title=Government announces reduced university plans for Zonqor|url=http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/56337/government_announces_reduced_university_plans_for_zonqor_#.VncO4PkrLIV|work=[[Malta Today]]|date=20 August 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010090820/http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/56337/government_announces_reduced_university_plans_for_zonqor_|archivedate=10 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 August, Muscat announced that the government had reached an agreement with the Sadeen Group that the campus be split between the former [[Malta Dockyard|Dock No. 1]] in [[Cospicua]] and a reduced site at \u017bonqor Point. The campus at \u017bonqor is much smaller than the one originally planned, and it will occupy the site of the water polo pitch and {{convert|18000|m2|abbr=on}} of adjoining ODZ fields. This campus is to consist of three faculties and student dormitories, with a maximum height of five stories. A new water polo pitch is also to be built to replace the one that will be demolished to make way for the university. The campus at Cospicua will occupy two former [[warehouse]]s at Dock No. 1 which were built during [[Knights Hospitaller|Hospitaller]] and [[British Empire|British]] rule. Additional buildings are to be constructed, but they are to keep with the architectural style of the area.<ref name=times2015-08-20>{{cite news|title='American' University to occupy Dock 1 buildings and reduced Zonqor site|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150820/local/update-3-american-university-to-occupy-dock-1-buildings-and-reduced.581335|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=20 August 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150911141423/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150820/local/update-3-american-university-to-occupy-dock-1-buildings-and-reduced.581335|archivedate=11 September 2015}}</ref> This restoration project is bringing an otherwise run down Dock no. 1 back on its feet, which had been abandoned with the end of the rule of the British. The government will rent out both campuses to Sadeen Group for around \u20ac200,000 a year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Government to rent public land to American University of Malta on the cheap|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2015-08-30/local-news/Government-to-rent-public-land-to-American-University-of-Malta-on-the-cheap-6736141281|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=30 August 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016154148/http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2015-08-30/local-news/Government-to-rent-public-land-to-American-University-of-Malta-on-the-cheap-6736141281|archivedate=16 October 2015}}</ref> \n\nFront \u0126arsien ODZ said that the proposal of splitting the campus was better than the original one, but said that it was still unacceptable to build on ODZ land.<ref name=times2015-08-20/> The [[University Students' Council (Malta)|University Students' Council]] also expressed its disappointment at the government building part of the campus at \u017bonqor Point.<ref>{{cite news|title=KSU disappointed by the governments adamant decision confirming the American University of Malta at Zonqor Point|url=http://www.ksu.org.mt/index.php/press/160-ksu-disappointed-by-the-governments-adamant-decision-confirming-the-american-university-of-malta-at-zonqor-point|work=[[University Students' Council (Malta)|KSU]]|date=28 September 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220212200/http://www.ksu.org.mt/index.php/press/160-ksu-disappointed-by-the-governments-adamant-decision-confirming-the-american-university-of-malta-at-zonqor-point|archivedate=20 December 2015}}</ref> On the other hand, the move was welcomed by the Cospicua Heritage Society, who said that the [[Three Cities]] and [[Kalkara]] would greatly benefit from the project.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cospicua Heritage Society qed tappo\u0121\u0121ja l-pro\u0121ett tal-universit\u00e0|url=http://www.inewsmalta.com/dart/20150824-cospicua-heritage-society-qed-tappo-ja-pro-ett-tal-universit|work=iNews Malta|date=24 August 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220234715/http://www.inewsmalta.com/dart/20150824-cospicua-heritage-society-qed-tappo-ja-pro-ett-tal-universit|archivedate=20 December 2015|language=Maltese}}</ref>\n\nThe government approved the granting of land for the AUM after a 15-hour long debate in parliament on 15 December 2015.<ref name=times2015-12-15>{{cite news|title=House approves 'American University' property motion after night-long debate|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20151215/local/aum-undergoing-rigorous-evaluation-education-minister.595847|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=15 December 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151219174151/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20151215/local/aum-undergoing-rigorous-evaluation-education-minister.595847|archivedate=19 December 2015}}</ref> Front \u0126arsien ODZ called this parliamentary sitting \"surreal\" and said that it shows terrible governance.<ref>{{cite news|title=Front slams vote for 'American University'|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20151216/local/front-slams-vote-for-american-university.595918|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=16 December 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151219175001/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20151216/local/front-slams-vote-for-american-university.595918|archivedate=19 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Malta - Cospicua - Fuq San l-Inkurunazzjoni - Dock no1 11 ies.jpg|thumb|The British Building at Dock No. 1 in Cospicua]]\n\nOn 25 August 2016, the Planning Authority approved the restoration of the British Building at Dock No. 1, and its conversion into a campus to house part of the AUM. Parts of the building which were destroyed during [[World War II]] will be rebuilt, while an intermediate level and a new second floor with a [[Contemporary architecture|contemporary]] glass-and-steel design will be constructed.<ref>{{cite web|title=University in Cospicua granted permit|url=http://www.pa.org.mt/news-details?id=1137|website=Planning Authority|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828114710/http://www.pa.org.mt/news-details?id=1137|archivedate=28 August 2016|date=25 August 2016}}</ref> The renovation of the building was entrusted to the architect Edwin Mintoff, to be completed by April 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Saliba|first1=Norma|title=American University buildings will reflect the past historic appearance of Cospicua Wharf|url=http://www.tvm.com.mt/en/news/il-binjiet-tal-uaameamerican-university-buildings-will-reflect-the-past-historic-appearance-of-cospicua-wharfrican-university-buildings-will-reflect-the-past-historic-appearance-of-cospicua-wharfm-se/|work=[[TVM (Malta)|TVM]]|date=26 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nThere are plans to restore the Knights' Building at Dock No. 1 and convert it into part of the campus, and this renovation is planned to be completed by 2017\u201318. The Marsaskala campus is to be ready by 2019\u201320.<ref name=\"times2016-09-25\"/>\n\n===Accreditation and licensing===\nIn December 2015, Leader of the Opposition [[Simon Busuttil]] stated that since the AUM applied for the licence of a \"Higher Education Institution\", its marketing of itself as a \"University\" is illegal.<ref name=times2015-12-15/> In January 2016, the National Commission for Further and Higher Education announced that Sadeen Education Investment Ltd had been given a licence to operate a Higher Education Institution under the name ''American Institute of Malta''. This was the first step in the process to acquire a university licence.<ref name=times2016-01-26>{{cite news|title=American University of Malta formally becomes American Institute of Malta, process to acquire university licence in process|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160126/local/american-university-of-malta-formally-becomes-american-institute-of.600155|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=26 January 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126174313/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160126/local/american-university-of-malta-formally-becomes-american-institute-of.600155|archivedate=26 January 2016}}</ref> The commission has stated that a degree issued by the American Institute would have the same value as one issued by the University of Malta.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ivan|title=American Institute's degree 'equivalent to university's'|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160201/local/american-institutes-degree-equivalent-to-universitys.600851|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=1 February 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201174356/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160201/local/american-institutes-degree-equivalent-to-universitys.600851|archivedate=1 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nHowever, on 11 March 2016, Sadeen Education Investment Ltd was notified by a judicial letter that licensed higher education institutions are prohibited from using the word \"university\" in their advertising and publicity, unless they have been granted that status formally.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vella|first1=Matthew|title=Watchdog fines Sadeen for marketing unlicensed 'university'|url=http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/63682/watchdog_fines_sadeen_over_aum_logo|work=Malta Today|date=3 April 2016}}</ref> On 6 May 2016, Economy Minister [[Christian Cardona]] said that he had \"no doubt that this will be a University and not an institute. This is part of a process, but the project will result in a University\".<ref name=\"Times0516\">{{cite news|last1=Martin|first1=Ivan|title=American Institute courses could start this year|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160506/local/american-institute-courses-could-start-this-year.611196|work=timesofmalta.com|date=6 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe National Commission for Further and Higher Education (NCFHE) officially accredited the AUM on 30 June 2016, after a 14-month process which included financial and academic evaluations. The commission imposed a number of conditions on the AUM, including an annual audit by the [[Clemson University]].<ref>{{cite news|title=American University of Malta gets accreditation at last|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160630/local/american-university-of-malta-gets-accreditation-at-last.617262|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=30 June 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701130607/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160630/local/american-university-of-malta-gets-accreditation-at-last.617262|archivedate=1 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Sansone|first1=Kurt|title=Conditions imposed on Sadeen Group for university licence 'are not negotiable'|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160703/local/conditions-imposed-on-sadeen-group-for-university-licence-are-not.617495|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=3 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703105715/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160703/local/conditions-imposed-on-sadeen-group-for-university-licence-are-not.617495|archivedate=3 July 2016}}</ref> Sadeen asked for a compromise on these conditions, but the commission insisted that they were not negotiable.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sansone|first1=Kurt|title=No university licence for Sadeen, one month before 'first student intake'|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160910/local/no-university-licence-for-sadeen-one-month-before-first-student-intake.624564|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=10 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910171108/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160910/local/no-university-licence-for-sadeen-one-month-before-first-student-intake.624564|archivedate=10 September 2016}}</ref> After the conditions were accepted, the commission issued a 5-year university licence on 16 September 2016.<ref name=\"ourbeginnings\">{{cite web|title=Our Beginnings|url=http://aum.edu.mt/en/article/5/Our-Beginnings|website=American University of Malta|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106002945/http://aum.edu.mt/en/article/5/Our-Beginnings|archivedate=6 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sadeen granted 5-year licence to run American University of Malta|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160919/local/sadeen-granted-5-year-licence-to-run-american-university-of-malta.625569|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=19 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920185425/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160919/local/sadeen-granted-5-year-licence-to-run-american-university-of-malta.625569|archivedate=20 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nTwo former employees of the National Commission for Further and Higher Education, both directly involved in the accreditation of the AUM, were hired by the university as lecturers in August 2019.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=American University of Malta Hires Two Lecturers from Its Own Education Regulator|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/american-university-of-malta-hires-two-lecturers-from-its-own-education-regulator/|work=Lovin Malta|date=13 August 2019}}</ref> One of the two former NCFHE employees hired by the AUM visited the campus for an inspection soon after the mass firing of faculty in January 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=Interview: The Man who came from Baku (3)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/08/interview-the-man-who-came-in-from-baku-3/|website=manueldelia.com|date=19 August 2019}}</ref> This episode became known as the accreditation-for-jobs scandal. Despite suspicions of ethical impropriety, an inquiry was never conducted.\n\n===Troubled tenure of founding provost===\nIn July 2019, Provost John Ryder announced his resignation, stating that he had fulfilled his contract with the AUM but would have \"loved not to have had some of the problems or [made some of the] mistakes\" he did.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=American University Of Malta\u2019s Head John Ryder Will Retire This Month|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/american-university-of-maltas-head-john-ryder-will-retire-this-month/|work=Lovin Malta|date=12 July 2019}}</ref> These mistakes included hiring too many faculty for the 2017-18 academic year, firing those same faculty en masse in January 2018, consistently hiding student enrolment figures to avoid media scrutiny and enacting poor quality assurance processes, resulting in the hiring of faculty who were guilty of academic plagiarism and degree fraud. Ryder was promptly replaced by another American higher education administrator, Jeremy Brown. \n\nRyder's decision to hire too many faculty before the first academic term and fire them without cause at the start of the second term damaged the institution's international reputation and complicated efforts to make cooperative agreements with other universities, even after his departure. [[Arkansas State University]] reconsidered its earlier decision to collaborate with the AUM on dual degree programs after uncovering former employees' negative comments on the site [[Glassdoor]] describing the mass termination event.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ivan|title=Concerns halt partnership between AUM and US university|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/concerns-halt-partnership-between-aum-and-us-university.733312|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=5 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=American University of Malta Company Reviews|url=https://www.glassdoor.com/Reviews/American-University-of-Malta-Reviews-E2075737.htm|work=[[Glassdoor]]|date=12 September 2019}}</ref> In an interview with investigative journalist Lizzie Eldridge, Ryder confessed that although he was not among the faculty fired in January 2018, it was still the \"worst day of my professional life by far.\"<ref>{{cite blog|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=Interview: The Man who came from Baku (3)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/08/interview-the-man-who-came-in-from-baku-3/|work=Truth be Told|date=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Criticisms==\nMembers of the Maltese political elite, media, civil society, academe and the diplomatic community have all raised critical questions about the university. Former AUM employees have also expressed concerns about the fledgling higher education institution.\n\n===Not American===\nOne criticism is that the AUM is not authentically American. The company behind the project is from Jordan, not the United States. Almost a year before her death, Maltese journalist [[Daphne Caruana Galizia]] noted that \"the man the Jordanian outfit has chosen to be rector of this questionable 'university' is John Ryder, who is the only American aspect of the project\" <ref>{{cite web|title=From Baku to the 'American University of Malta'|url=https://daphnecaruanagalizia.com/2016/09/baku-american-university-malta/|website=daphnecaruanagalizia.com|date=September 25, 2016}}</ref> In 2018, the AUM hired an American president, Lewis N. Walker, as well.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Attard|first1=Rachel|title=Plans on Zonqor will only start when Dock 1 campus nears full capacity \u2013 new AUM president|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2018-02-25/local-news/Plans-on-Zonqor-will-only-start-when-Dock-1-campus-nears-full-capacity-new-AUM-president-6736185288|work=Malta Independent|date=February 25, 2018}}</ref>   \n\nIn a series of articles on the AUM, titled 'When is a University not a University?,' investigative journalist Lizzie Eldridge suggested that one possible explanation for why the AUM retains its American identity is to \"maintain appearances\" as a legitimate higher education enterprise: \"Sometimes, as, for example, in instances of money laundering, where a company is deliberately set up as a front, appearances are crucial.\" <ref>{{cite blog|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=When is a university not a university? (3)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/06/when-is-a-university-not-a-university-3/|work=manueldelia.com|date=June 6, 2019}}</ref> Rumours that the AUM selectively recruited U.S. citizens to make the institution appear American are substantiated by an ex-staff member who claimed that in a Skype interview with provost John Ryder, he was told that \u2018the main thing you have going for you is that you\u2019re American.\u2019 <ref>{{cite blog|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=When is a university not a university? (1)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/06/when-is-a-university-not-a-university-1/|website=manueldelia.com|date=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nPhilip G. Altbach, Boston College faculty member and director of the Center for International Higher Education, expressed concern that institutions such as Sadeen-owned AUM are \"business interests starting universities to make money using the American brand.\" <ref>{{cite news|last1=Jaschik|first1=Scott|title=Is Newest 'American U. of...' Really American?|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/05/11/questions-raised-about-whether-american-u-malta-really-american|work=[[Inside Higher Ed]]|date=May 11, 2015}}</ref> \n\nWhen asked in an interview about her views concerning the controversial American university in Malta, outgoing U.S. Ambassador to Malta [[G. Kathleen Hill]] insisted \"It's not American...it's not an American initiative but an initiative by the Sadeen Group which is out of Jordan.\" <ref>{{cite interview|title='The United States is more than President Trump'|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20180930/interview/the-united-states-is-more-than-president-trump.690344|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=September 30, 2018}}</ref> \n\nTo this criticism, the AUM's provost John Ryder responded that the university is \"not a brand or offshoot, or run by any American university ... [but it is] American in curriculum and organisation.\"<ref name=\"times2016-09-25\">{{cite news|last1=Sansone|first1=Kurt|title=AUM owner aspires for 'higher education diamond in the Mediterranean'|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160925/local/diamond-waiting-to-shine.625996|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=25 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160926161256/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160925/local/diamond-waiting-to-shine.625996|archivedate=26 September 2016}}</ref> The curricula are officially provided by DePaul University, Chicago. A spokesperson for DePaul University issued a statement, qualifying the legitimacy of AUM's curricula: \"Faculty designed degree programs in areas that were requested, with the dual goals of being academically well-designed and meeting regulatory requirements in Malta. Individual faculty members were selected with the help of teams -- composed of associate deans, school directors and department chairs -- in the relevant colleges. Faculty then were asked to design the curriculum, and they were compensated for their work,\" also adding; \"[t]he right to use our name (DePaul University) is specifically in connection to the curriculum. While specifics of any DePaul contract are proprietary, I can tell you that it went through the usual, internal multi-step review process.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jaschik|first1=Scott|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/05/11/questions-raised-about-whether-american-u-malta-really-american|title=Questions raised about whether American U. of Malta is really American|work=[[Inside Higher Ed]]|date= 11 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Lack of transparency and violation of public trust===\nCriticism has also been levelled at the AUM and Maltese Labour government for keeping the contents of its agreements secret from the Maltese public. Maltese Prime Minister Joseph Muscat was accused of a lack of transparency with regard to how government agreements with Sadeen were made.  He responded by saying that the public was informed on the first occasion.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u2018I can\u2019t see how I can be more transparent\u2019|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150517/interview/i-cant-see-how-i-can-be-more-transparent.568415|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=17 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220212411/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150517/interview/i-cant-see-how-i-can-be-more-transparent.568415|archivedate=20 December 2015}}</ref> NGOs have called for the publication of the agreement between the government and Sadeen Group.<ref>{{cite news|title=NGOs urge publication of Sadeen deal for university|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20151103/local/ngos-urge-publication-of-sadeen-deal-for-university.590697|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=3 November 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220214744/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20151103/local/ngos-urge-publication-of-sadeen-deal-for-university.590697|archivedate=20 December 2015}}</ref> A pressing concern is that without full transparency, the government's agreed-upon terms could serve the interests of Sadeen, while costing the Maltese taxpayer and undermining public trust.\n\nFormer AUM employees have criticized the AUM for its lack of transparency. A former staff member has called the AUM's social media and marketing campaigns \"smoke and mirrors,\" meant to hide the \"AUM\u2019s activities...from the public eye, behind a Facebook page designed to make you believe you\u2019ve entered an idyllic higher education wonderland, in which it\u2019s nearly impossible to distinguish between fiction and fact, fantasy and reality, glitz and horror.\" <ref>{{cite web|title='Smoke and mirrors: The personal account of an AUM staff member'|url=https://theshiftnews.com/2019/03/02/smoke-and-mirrors-the-personal-account-of-an-aum-staff-member/|work=The Shift News|date=28 February 2019}}</ref> A former lecturer at the AUM cited a confidentiality clause in the institution's standard employment contract that restricts transparency by threatening punitive measures against employees who leak information to the media. The lecturer reports: \"There was a confidentiality clause which stated that we would have to pay back twice our yearly salary, if we broke it\u2014a provision that is quite bizarre in America, and unheard of in Malta.\" <ref>{{cite web|title='Promise and Betrayal: Former American University of Malta Lecturer Speaks Out'|url=http://www.islesoftheleft.org/promise-betrayal-a-former-american-university-of-malta-lecturer-speaks-out|work=Isles of the Left|date=31 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, the AUM's plans to develop protected land in Zonqor, which were previously a  matter of public record, disappeared from the Malta Planning Authority website. This event coincided with the Planning Authority's adoption of a new policy to only disclose documents which are part of completed development applications. So long as the AUM maintains an incomplete application, it can effectively hide from public view the planning documents for the controversial second campus at Zonqor Point. The Planning Authority's policy has since come under scrutiny by the Ombudsman. <ref>{{cite news|title=\u2018Ombudsman asked to investigate restriction on information on planning website\u2019|url=|work=[[Malta_Today]]|date=8 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Locating university in higher education saturated Malta===\nThe Maltese government has also been criticized for permitting AUM, a foreign university, to establish itself in the small country of Malta, which is already home to several higher education institutions.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mayo|first1=Peter|title=Of Universities, Monopolies, and Public Goods|journal=Think|url=http://www.um.edu.mt/think/of-universities-monopolies-and-public-goods/|publisher=[[University of Malta]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220183841/http://www.um.edu.mt/think/of-universities-monopolies-and-public-goods/|archivedate=20 December 2015}}</ref> The government stated that the AUM would end the monopoly that the [[University of Malta]] has on higher education.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lindsay|first1=David|title=Government seeking to end University of Malta\u2019s \u2018monopoly\u2019|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2015-05-03/local-news/Government-seeking-to-end-University-of-Malta-s-monopoly-6736134834|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=3 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150807015710/http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2015-05-03/local-news/Government-seeking-to-end-University-of-Malta-s-monopoly-6736134834|archivedate=7 August 2015}}</ref> In response to this, lecturers at the University of Malta disagreed with the use of the term \"monopoly\", stating that the university already competes with other institutions such as [[MCAST]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Lecturers rubbish PM's claim of university monopoly|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150520/local/lecturers-rubbish-pms-claim-of-university-monopoly.568972|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=20 May 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150522183824/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20150520/local/lecturers-rubbish-pms-claim-of-university-monopoly.568972|archivedate=22 May 2015}}</ref> The Maltese Ministry of Education has supported other foreign higher education start-ups in Malta, for instance, Global College and Woolf University.<ref>{{cite web|title=\nStudy World Global College Malta|url=http://www.swehg.com/swgcm/|date=2016}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=\nOxford researcher seeks Malta accreditation for world\u2019s first \u2018Blockchain University\u2019|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/oxford-researcher-seeks-malta-accreditation-for-worlds-first-blockchain-university/|work=Lovin Malta|date=27 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Faculty recruitment for accreditation purposes only===\nMaltese blogger and political commentator Manuel Delia and a dismissed AUM lecturer criticised the Maltese accreditor and the AUM, alleging that the initial recruitment of faculty, including several highly qualified academics from the United States and Britain, \"was a scam to demonstrate academic prowess to the National Council for Further and Higher Education in order to acquire accreditation.\" <ref>{{cite web|last1=Delia|first1=Manuel|title=Martin Scicluna's commission duped by AUM\u2014former lecturer|url=https://manueldelia.com/2018/06/martin-sciclunas-commission-duped-by-aum-former-lecturer/|website=manueldelia.com|date=1 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Promise and Betrayal: Former American University of Malta Lecturer Speaks Out|url=http://www.islesoftheleft.org/promise-betrayal-a-former-american-university-of-malta-lecturer-speaks-out|work=Isles of the Left|date=31 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=AUM Spotlight|url=https://twitter.com/AUM_Spotlight|website=twitter.com|date=3 June 2018}}</ref> In the aftermath of the mass firing event in January 2018, new faculty demonstrated reduced qualifications, received significantly lower salaries and, in at least four cases, were guilty of ethical improprieties of which their predecessors were not.<ref>{{cite news|title=Disgraced lecturer forced to leave AUM after reports of plagiarism|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20180203/local/disgraced-lecturer-forced-to-leave-aum-after-reports-of-plagiarism.669611|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=3 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=American University of Malta Lecturer Suspected of Lying About His Oxford PhD|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/news-breaking/breaking-american-university-of-malta-lecturer-suspected-of-lying-about-his-oxford-phd|work=Lovin Malta|date=12 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=American University of Malta Hires Two Lecturers from Its Own Education Regulator|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/american-university-of-malta-hires-two-lecturers-from-its-own-education-regulator/|work=Lovin Malta|date=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Negative impact on cultural heritage, quality of life and public space===\nDespite government projections that the AUM project would improve the social and economic situation of southern Malta, Media coverage points to the university's negative impact on the local Bormla community and the greater Three Cities region. Reports indicate declining quality of life and reduced public access to open space and cultural heritage sites. \n\nExpressing a concern \"to safeguard the public interest\" by preserving open spaces and historical sites, the Partit Demokratiku opposed the university's application filed with planning authorities to expand the Dock 1 campus into the nearby Cottonera district, including a student dormitory, underground parking garage and a rooftop pool.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2019-03-23/local-news/PD-to-safeguard-public-interest-in-relation-to-AUM-extension-6736205530|title=PD 'to safeguard public interest' in relation to AUM extension|work=Malta Independent|date=23 March 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn March 2019, Maltese environmental NGO Flimkien g\u0127al Ambjent A\u0127jar warned that the planned extension of the AUM campus would effectively privatise the majority of public space along the Bormla waterfront and destroy cultural landmarks. \"Such a building in this historically and visually sensitive area should be restored and rehabilitated through best practice and not simply bulldozed to make way for incompatible uses to the detriment of cultural heritage.\" <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20190328/local/planned-aum-extension-will-have-direct-detrimental-impact-on-cottonera.705806|title=Planned AUM extension will have 'direct detrimental impact' on Cottonera, FAA warns|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=28 March 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn September 2019, citizens in the Three Cities region formed the civil action group ''Azzjoni: Tuna Artna Lura'' (Maltese for ''Action: Give Us Back Our Land'') and started a petition to oppose the AUM's planned construction of a dormitory between the British and Knights Buildings, which would deprive the community of public space and a heritage site.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/cottonera-residents-form-action-group-to-oppose-aum-dorm-plans.732850|title=American University Malta's extension plans opposed by residents, PN|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=3 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2019-09-03/local-news/Civil-action-group-urges-people-to-sign-petition-against-AUM-expansion-6736213036|title=Civil action group urges people to sign petition against AUM expansion|work=Malta Independent|date=3 September 2019}}</ref> In a protest video, activists demonstrated the graphic damage the AUM's expansion would inflict upon the heritage site, superimposing the planned buildings on top of iconic European landmarks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/watch-cottonera-activists-use-paris-and-rome-to-make-their-point.749299|title=Watch: Cottonera activists use Paris and Rome to make their point|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=12 November 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn 19 November 2019, the Environmental Commission of the Catholic Church in Malta (Curia) publicly declared its opposition to the AUM extension, citing its deleterious effects on Cottonera resident wellbeing and heritage protection: \u201cThe application to occupy some of the few remaining open spaces in the heart of Cottonera, in order to accommodate facilities for AUM, is a clear example of these dangers [to quality of life and heritage preservation]. When so many doubts have been expressed about the need or even the usefulness of these facilities, and when they are evidently not in the best interest of the people of Cottonera, one cannot but be gravely concerned about who is being served by planning in this country.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|last1=Costa|first1=Massimo|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/98738/aum_extension_threatens_residents_wellbeing_and_areas_historical_heritage_curia_warns#.XdbQKVdKjIU|title=AUM extension threatens residents' wellbeing and area's historical heritage, Curia warns|work=[[Malta Today]]|date=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn response to pressure from activists and political leaders, the Maltese Planning Authority rejected the AUM's proposed extension to the campus on the Dock 1 site, citing the need to preserve cultural heritage, maintain public open space and ensure the continued view of the Gates of Fort St. Michael from Bormla, which would have been blocked by the planned building.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Debono|first1=James|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/environment/townscapes/97671/planning_authority_american_university_extension_decision#.XY6bl25uLIV|title=Planning Authority to reject American University extension|work=[[Malta Today]]|date=26 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Inadequate quality assurance===\nThe AUM has also been criticised for its poor quality assurance practices. Currently the AUM is accredited by the Maltese National Commission for Further and Higher Education, but has not been able to meet the more rigorous standards of U.S. accreditation.<ref>{{cite news|title=American University of Malta gets accreditation at last|url=http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160630/local/american-university-of-malta-gets-accreditation-at-last.617262|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=30 June 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701130607/http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160630/local/american-university-of-malta-gets-accreditation-at-last.617262|archivedate=1 July 2016}}</ref> \n\nIn at least two instances, Provost John Ryder and Quality Assurance Manager Rania Allam failed to meet minimum quality assurance standards for recruitment and hiring. Soon after the mass firing of faculty in January 2018, the AUM recruited, hired and employed a lecturer with a history of committing plagiarism, clearly having violated the principle of academic integrity.<ref>{{cite news|title=Disgraced lecturer forced to leave AUM after reports of plagiarism|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20180203/local/disgraced-lecturer-forced-to-leave-aum-after-reports-of-plagiarism.669611|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=3 February 2018}}</ref> Due to inadequate quality assurance, Ryder and Allam allowed a second faculty member, fraudulently claiming to hold academic credentials he did not, to join the AUM faculty.<ref>{{cite news|title=American University of Malta Lecturer Suspected of Lying About His Oxford PhD|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/news-breaking/breaking-american-university-of-malta-lecturer-suspected-of-lying-about-his-oxford-phd|work=Lovin Malta|date=12 February 2018}}</ref> \n\nInvestigative journalist Lizzie Eldridge has noted how the AUM's mass dismissal of faculty combined with poor quality assurance in hiring replacement faculty normalises unethical practices for new enterprises in Malta: \"It becomes normal for a \u2018start-up\u2019 university to engage in mass firings of their newly employed and highly qualified staff and then hire both a plagiarist and a fraud.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=Guest Series: Pandora's Box (3)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/09/guest-series-pandoras-box-3/|website=manueldelia.com|date=29 September 2019}}</ref>     \n\nIn August 2019, two former employees of the Maltese National Commission for Further and Higher Education, both directly involved in the AUM's accreditation process, were hired by the university as lecturers, suggesting the possibility of a revolving door or quid pro quo arrangement between the accreditor and the AUM.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=American University of Malta Hires Two Lecturers from Its Own Education Regulator|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/american-university-of-malta-hires-two-lecturers-from-its-own-education-regulator/|work=Lovin Malta|date=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=Interview: The Man who came from Baku (3)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/08/interview-the-man-who-came-in-from-baku-3/|website=manueldelia.com|date=19 August 2019}}</ref> \n\nUniversity of Malta Education Professor and public intellectual Peter Mayo described the difficulty of obtaining US accreditation with poor quality assurance practices as the AUM's primary obstacle to becoming a legitimate higher education institution: \"The main struggle for institutions such as the new AUM, situated on an island at the heart of the Mediterranean, strategically posed [sic] to attract students from North Africa and Europe, is, not only to attract an adequate number of students (this has been incredibly low to the extent that some recruited academics were dismissed before the end of their probation period), but, one would imagine, to establish links with US universities and perhaps seek accreditation from important USA agencies.\" <ref>{{cite news|last1=Mayo|first1=Peter|title=US Higher Education Influence Takes a Different Turn|url=https://www.counterpunch.org/2019/03/22/110244/|work=[[CounterPunch]]|date=22 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe AUM has still not been able to obtain U.S. accreditation.\n\n==Controversies==\nIn the first two years of the AUM's existence, the higher education institution has been plagued by a number of controversies.  Despite the university's small student body, high employee turnover and growing legal troubles, Malta's Education Minister [[Evarist Bartolo]] insisted that the AUM is not entirely a  \u201cgarage operation\u201d <ref>{{cite news|last1=Grech|first1=Helena|title=Minister would rather see the American University of Malta 'start small, grow gradually'|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2017-11-13/local-news/Education-Minister-would-rather-see-AUM-start-small-grow-gradually-6736181366|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=13 November 2017}}</ref> \n\n===Suspicions of corruption, kickbacks and quid pro quo===\nIn 2019, Maltese Prime Minister Joseph Muscat, who had persuaded Hani Saleh to locate the university in Malta, was named by the [[Organized Crime and Corruption Reporting Project]] (OCCRP) as 'man of the year in organised crime and corruption'.<ref>{{cite news |title=Joseph Muscat named \u20182019 man of the year in organised crime and corruption\u2019 |url=https://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2019-12-27/local-news/Joseph-Muscat-named-2019-man-of-the-year-in-organised-crime-and-corruption-6736217841 |accessdate=26 March 2020 |work=The Malta Independent |date=December 27, 2019}}</ref> In 2020, immediately prior to the ascension of Muscat's successor, [[Robert Abela]], it was discovered that \u20ac20,000 airline tickets to Dubai, used by Muscat, his wife and children for a recent family vacation, were purchased in Jordan, provoking suspicion that they constituted a kickback from Sadeen Group for the AUM concessions.<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Muscat|first1=Caroline|url=https://theshiftnews.com/2020/01/07/tickets-to-dubai-for-joseph-muscats-family-were-purchased-in-jordan/|title=Tickets to Dubai for Joseph Muscat\u2019s family were purchased in Jordan|work=The Shift News|date=7 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe Maltese press also raised concerns that the National Commission for Further and Higher Education (NCFHE) turned a blind eye to the mass dismissal of faculty in January 2018 in a quid pro quo arrangement with the AUM. Two former employees of the NCFHE, both directly involved in the AUM's accreditation, were hired as lecturers by the university in August 2019, less than two years after the dismissal of the university's entire faculty: \"Manuel Vella Rago was until recently Head of Quality Assurance at NCFHE, while Audrey Abela was its Head of Accreditation, both key roles in the regulation of the AUM.\" <ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=American University of Malta Hires Two Lecturers from Its Own Education Regulator|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/american-university-of-malta-hires-two-lecturers-from-its-own-education-regulator/|work=Lovin Malta|date=13 August 2019}}</ref> According to investigative journalist Lizzie Eldridge, \"Manuel Vella Rago\u2019s previous position [was not only] as Head of Quality Assurance at the NCFHE,  . . . he was [also] one of the inspectors who made that \u2018surprise visit\u2019 to the AUM last year [soon after the mass firing of the AUM's faculty in January 2018].\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=Interview: The Man who came from Baku (3)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/08/interview-the-man-who-came-in-from-baku-3/|website=manueldelia.com|date=19 August 2019}}</ref> In spite of these revelations, no investigation of the accreditation-for-jobs scandal was ever initiated.\n\n===Low student enrolments and inability to achieve targets===\nIn the AUM's first two years, refusals by then-Provost John Ryder to publicly release the official enrollment figures was a recurring flashpoint of controversy. An early promotional video presented the new university's plan to admit 1,000 students in its first year, eventually reaching a total enrollment of 4,000 students by its fourth year.<ref>{{YouTube|id=Y01mF8p13tk|title=AUM Promo Video}}</ref> \n\nThe AUM officially began offering classes on Tuesday September 12, 2017, rather than Monday September 11, to avoid association with the [[September 11 attacks]] anniversary.<ref name=\"maltachamber\">{{cite news|title=AUM Opens its Doors to the First Batch of Students|url=http://www.maltachamber.org.mt/page.aspx?rid=8697&preview=1&c=95493AB4B36E9D8D6637317593DB929F7C5700C8&k=-534249962|work=maltachamber.org.mt|date=12 September 2017}}</ref> Asked how many students the AUM admitted for the Fall semester (academic year 2017-18), then-Provost Ryder would only say that student recruitment was \u201cproving to be challenging.\" <ref>{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ivan|title=AUM student enrolment is 'proving challenging', provost says|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20170906/local/aum-student-enrolment-is-proving-challenging-provost-says.657269|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=6 September 2017}}</ref> In November of the same year, the [[Times of Malta]] reported that the AUM's revised plan was to enroll 330 students in its first semester, but the \"university managed to attract 15 students.\"<ref name=\"timesofmalta1\">{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ivan|title=AUM firing staff after failing to attract students|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20171112/local/aum-firing-staff-after-failing-to-attract-students.662834|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=12 November 2017}}</ref> The figure was denied by university officials.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schembri Orland|first1=Kevin|title=AUM says it has more than 15 students, but still doesn't divulge number|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2017-11-19/local-news/AUM-says-it-has-more-than-15-students-but-still-doesn-t-divulge-number-6736181619|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=19 November 2017}}</ref> Four days later, Ryder acknowledged in a [[Television Malta]] interview that the AUM student body numbered 23.<ref>{{cite news|title=AUM rector says original targets were not realistic but is confident for the future|url=https://www.tvm.com.mt/en/news/aum-rector-says-original-targets-were-not-realistic-but-is-confident-for-the-future/|work=[[Television Malta]]|date=24 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt the start of the subsequent academic year (2018\u201319), the AUM's provost and the director of student recruitment only disclosed the number of countries from which it received applications, but not the total numbers of applicants or enrolments.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sansone|first1=Kurt|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/89051/aum_will_not_divulge_number_of_new_students_yet#.XDHRzUxFzmI|title=American University of Malta will not divulge number of new students yet|work=MaltaToday|date=27 August 2018}}</ref> Despite then-Provost Ryder's promises to eventually share enrolment figures with the media, none were ever officially released. An anonymous source at the university divulged to the [[Times of Malta]] that six new students had been admitted in the fledgling institution's second year of operations.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ivan|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20180916/local/only-six-new-students-enrolled-at-aum-so-far.689221|title=Only six new students enrolled at AUM so far|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=16 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn his role as Chairman of the Cottonera Rehabilitation Committee, Maltese Parliament Member and Labour Party insider [[Glenn Bedingfield]] expressed scepticism that the AUM would fulfil its contractual obligation with the Government of Malta to reach the agreed-upon number of students four years after the building phase of the Cospicua campus is completed: \"I am beginning to doubt whether they [the AUM] will ever be able to attract the 4,000 students in the promised timeframe [2025 to 2029].\" <ref>{{cite news|last1=Bedingfield|first1=Glenn|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/aum-give-us-back-our-land-glenn-bedingfield.729326|title=AUM: Give us back our land|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=18 August 2019}}</ref> On the 13 October 2019, the [[Times of Malta]] reported that the AUM had only recruited one-fifth of the targeted number of students, 143 of the 710 it had promised the Maltese government.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Micallef|first1=Keith|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/aum-student-population-fifth-of-promised-number.746091|title=AUM student population is a fifth of promised number|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Mass dismissals and other personnel decisions===\nAUM personnel decisions have also generated controversy, raising concerns about the legality of the new institution's employment policies and practices. Within a period of seven months, the employment contracts of 10 university employees were terminated, either by [[dismissal (employment)|dismissal]] or resignation: (1) Deputy (Construction Project) Manager (dismissal), (2) Admissions Director (dismissal), (3) Marketing and Public Relations Director (dismissal), (4) Vice President for Administrative Affairs (dismissal), (5) IT Technician (dismissal), (6) Webmaster (resignation), (7) Admissions Counselor (resignation), (8) Human Resources Director (dismissal), (9) Professor of Finance (dismissal) and (10) Dean of Student Affairs (resignation).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=This is What the American University of Malta Looks Like Two Years Later|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/news-breaking/this-is-what-the-american-university-of-malta-looks-like-two-years-later|work=lovinmalta.com|date=11 November 2017}}</ref> \n\nSeveral of these terminations precipitated legal action by ex-employees against the university. The dismissed deputy manager filed a judicial protest against Sadeen Education.<ref>{{cite news|title=American University of Malta deputy manager says claims against him were fabricated|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20170523/local/american-university-deputy-manager-says-claims-against-him-were.648810|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=23 May 2017}}</ref> The former admissions director sued the university for unfair dismissal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Couple file judicial protest claiming unfair dismissal by Sadeen Education Investment Ltd|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2017-10-20/local-news/Couple-file-judicial-protest-claiming-unfair-dismissal-by-Sadeen-Education-Investment-Ltd-6736180457|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=20 October 2017}}</ref> In a judicial protest, the former Assistant Director of Admissions alleged that the AUM fraudulently misrepresented salaries to prospective hires (wage agreed to in Euros but remunerated in U.S. Dollars), mismanaged the student recruitment process and, upon completion of the employees' service, failed to pay final salaries in full, \"presumably from loss of currency exchange.\" <ref>{{cite news|title=In judicial protest, former assistant director at AUM claims breach of contract|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2018-02-21/local-news/In-judicial-protest-former-assistant-director-at-AUM-claims-breach-of-contract-6736185146|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=21 February 2018}}</ref>   \n\nOn 4 January 2018, Provost John Ryder informed the 12 remaining AUM faculty members by e-mail that their employment with the university had been terminated without cause.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=BREAKING: American University of Malta Has Sacked All Its Faculty|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/news-breaking/breaking-american-university-of-malta-has-sacked-all-its-faculty|work=lovinmalta.com|date=4 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=AUM full time lecturers said to have been 'dismissed by email'|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2018-01-04/local-news/AUM-full-time-lectures-said-to-have-been-dismissed-by-email-6736183231|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=4 January 2018}}</ref> Five of the terminated faculty members sued the AUM for unfair dismissal and abuse of the six-month probationary period rule.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=Sued! Fresh Hell For American University of Malta as Five Sacked Lecturers Spill the Beans|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/sued-fresh-hell-for-american-university-of-malta-as-five-sacked-lecturers-spill-the-beans|work=lovinmalta.com|date=1 May 2018}}</ref> According to Maltese [[Labour law]], the six-month probationary rule stipulates that \"[t]he first six months of any employment under a contract of service is deemed to be probationary employment, unless otherwise agreed by both parties for a shorter probation period. [...] During the probationary period, either party may terminate the employment at will without reason. Provided that a week\u2019s notice of the termination of employment has to be given to the other party in the case of an employee who has been in the employment of the same employer continuously for more than one month.\" <ref>{{cite web|title=Malta Labour Law|url=http://www.fbsmalta.com/malta-labour-law/|website=www.fbsmalta.com|date=1 January 2012}}</ref> The five lecturers reached an agreement with Sadeen to settle the case before it reached adjudication, the terms of which were never made public. Arkansas State University, which signed an agreement with the AUM in March 2019 to offer dual degree programs, decided in September 2019 to freeze and scrutinize the AUM agreement after discovery of the mass firing of faculty in January 2018.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sansone|first1=Kurt|title=AUM signs collaborative agreement with Arkansas State University|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/business/business_news/93784/aum_signs_collaborative_agreement_with_arkansas_state_university#.XW5P4PZuLIU|work=maltatoday.com.mt|date=22 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Watson|first1=Gordon|title=AUM deal with Arkansas State University frozen after nearly all staff dismissed|url=https://www.newsbook.com.mt/artikli/2019/09/02/aum-deal-with-arkansas-state-university-frozen-after-nearly-all-staff-dismissed/?lang=en|work=newsbook.com.mt|date=2 September 2019}}</ref>  \n\nIn a two hour interview with investigative journalist Lizzie Eldridge, soon-to-be-retired Provost John Ryder admitted that the mistake that led to the mass dismissal of faculty from the AUM in January 2018 was his own, an error in forecasting the number of students, courses and instructors required for the first academic year: \"Part of the problem was that we were way overstaffed because I had hired with certain assumptions about the number of students and we weren\u2019t even in the neighbourhood for the first intake of students . . . It turned out to be much more difficult than we thought. We were way over-optimistic about recruiting and hiring.\" <ref>{{cite blog|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=Interview: The Man who came from Baku (3)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/08/interview-the-man-who-came-in-from-baku-3/|work=Truth be Told|date=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, despite a significant shortfall in projected enrolments and the fresh memory of the 2018 mass firing of faculty, the institution tweeted: \"We are proud to have grown our student numbers over the years and we are even more proud that we still cultivate strong relationships between students and professors.\" <ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/aumalta?lang=en |website=American University of Malta |publisher=Twitter |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> \n\n===Legal and ethical wrongdoing by board of trustees members===\nAnother source  of controversy is the alleged legal and ethical wrongdoing by members of the AUM's board of trustees. The board members are (1) [[Prince Jean of Luxembourg]] (chair), (2) [[John Ryder (scholar)]], (3) Taddeo Scerri (chairman of the board at the [[Bank of Valletta]]), (4) Hani Salah (Chief Executive Officer of Sadeen Group), (5) [[Taher al-Masri]], (6) [[Derrick Gosselin]] and (7) Carine Boonen.<ref name=\"timesofmalta2\">{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ivan|title=American University of Malta appoints Adrian Hillman as trustee|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20171029/local/american-university-of-malta-appoints-adrian-hillman-as-trustee.661617|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=29 October 2017}}</ref> \n\nBoard member Taddeo Scerri was accused of ignoring conflicts of interest between his AUM board appointment and his current and past professional positions in Malta's financial sector.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ivan|title=No conflict of interest with American University of Malta appointment, says BOV chair|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20171103/local/no-conflict-of-interest-with-american-university-of-malta.662085|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=3 November 2017}}</ref> \n\nBoard member Derrick Gosselin exploited a so-called [[Revolving door (politics)]] between an executive position in a private energy company and a senior policy position in the Flemish government in order to unethically influence public policy for his employer's financial benefit.<ref>{{cite report|author=Greens/EFA Group in the European Parliament|title=Revolving Doors and the Fossil Fuel Industry|url=https://issuu.com/europeecologie/docs/report_of_revolving_doors_digital|page=45|date=May 2, 2018}}</ref> \n\nBoard member John Ryder, who was appointed immediately after his resignation as provost, undertook the mass firing of faculty in January 2018 as well as hiring replacement faculty with histories of plagiarism and fraud in the aftermath.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Diacono|first1=Tim|title=BREAKING: American University of Malta Has Sacked All Its Faculty|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/news-breaking/breaking-american-university-of-malta-has-sacked-all-its-faculty|work=lovinmalta.com|date=4 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Disgraced lecturer forced to leave AUM after reports of plagiarism|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20180203/local/disgraced-lecturer-forced-to-leave-aum-after-reports-of-plagiarism.669611|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=3 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=American University of Malta Lecturer Suspected of Lying About His Oxford PhD|url=https://lovinmalta.com/news/news-breaking/breaking-american-university-of-malta-lecturer-suspected-of-lying-about-his-oxford-phd|work=Lovin Malta|date=12 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 January 2020, Adrian Hillman, former Allied Group managing director, was removed from his role as the government's representative to the AUM board.  A spokesperson for the Maltese Ministry of Education stated, \"Mr Adrian Hillman will no longer be the Government nominee on AUM.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carabott|first1=Sarah|last2=Xuereb|first2=Matthew|title=Adrian Hillman loses gaming authority contracts, AUM board role|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/hillmans-contract-with-gaming-authority-terminated-in-zero-tolerance.765615|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=23 January 2020}}</ref> Three years prior, Hillman was appointed to the board of trustees while under criminal investigation for laundering money and receiving kickbacks from the Maltese Prime Minister's chief of staff [[Keith Schembri]], who has been implicated in the [[Panama Papers]] money laundering scheme and the assassination of investigative journalist [[Daphne Caruana Galizia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Allied Group managing director Adrian Hillman denies allegations|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20160313/local/allied-group-managing-director-adrian-hillman-denies-allegations.605632|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=13 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"timesofmalta2\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Borg|first1=Jacob|last2=Grech|first2=Herman|title=Middleman's letter links Schembri and Fenech to Daphne murder|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/letter-links-schembri-and-fenech-to-daphne-murder.754435|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=2 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Difficulties with real estate company and construction contractors===\nIn the process of restoring the Dock 1 site, Sadeen has ignited controversy through its mismanagement of the construction project. After disappointingly low student enrolments, Sadeen sued a Maltese real estate company from which it purchased a hostel to serve as a student dormitory.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cocks|first1=Paul|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/90336/american_university_of_malta_tries_to_nullify_27_million_purchase_of_tarxien_hostel#.XDHJUUxFzmI|title=American University of Malta tries to nullify \u20ac2.7 million purchase of Tarxien hostel|work=Malta Today|date=23 Oct 2018}}</ref> Physical violence and threats of gun violence also ensued on the AUM campus between a contractor and subcontractor, with no intervention by campus security despite the threat posed to students, faculty and staff.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brincat|first1=Edwina|url=https://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20181203/local/contractors-come-to-blows-at-american-university-man-arraigned-after.695810|title=Contractors come to blows at American university, man arraigned after year-long search|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=3 Dec 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Poor community relations and backlash===\nDespite initial support from the local Bormla council, the AUM's continued expansion in the Dock 1 area has soured relations with some members of the Cospicua community. Citing increased traffic congestion and a shortage of vehicle parking caused by the new university's presence, Bormla's mayor requested that the university allow local residents to use 50% of the AUM's parking spaces in a planned underground complex. <ref>{{cite news|last1=Debono|first1=James|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/93722/american_university_parking_spaces_should_be_given_to_bormla_residents_mayor_says|title=American University parking spaces should be given to Borlma residents, mayor says|work=[[Malta Today]]|date=21 March 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe daughter of Malta's former prime minister Dom Mintoff, Yanna Mintoff, filed a protest with planning authorities to the proposed \"privatisation\" of public space by the AUM, warning against premature campus growth \"considering the very low uptake of the AUM educational services to date, and the lack of any positive multiplier effect on the local community and the country as a whole.\" <ref>{{cite news|last1=Debono|first1=James|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/environment/townscapes/94335/yana_mintoff_files_objection_to_american_university_expansion_in_bormla#.XLXGgPZuLmI|title=Yana Mintoff files objection to American University expansion in Bormla|work=[[Malta Today]]|date=16 April 2019}}</ref> Member of Parliament Glenn Bedingfield complained that the proposed student dormitory to be built as an extension to the Knights Building is \"too big for AUM's dozen students.\" <ref>{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Neil|url=https://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2019-08-08/local-news/Proposed-dormitory-too-big-for-AUM-s-dozen-students-MP-Gel-Bedingfield-says-6736211961|title=Proposed dormitory 'too big for AUM's dozen students,' MP Glenn Bedingfield says|work=Malta Independent|date=8 August 2019}}</ref> \n\nOn 26 September 2019, the Maltese Planning Authority board decided to reject the AUM's decision to extend the campus on the Dock 1 site, citing concerns that the building would obstruct the view of Fort St. Michael, reduce public open space and damage the social fabric of the community, thereby transforming \"Bormla into Sadeen town.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Debono|first1=James|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/environment/townscapes/97671/planning_authority_american_university_extension_decision#.XY6bl25uLIV|title=Planning Authority to reject American University extension|work=[[Malta Today]]|date=26 September 2019}}</ref> \n\nPalumbo Group, which operates the nearby dockyard, requested a court injunction to stop the AUM from blocking the parking entrance to Dock 1. \"The university cannot close off the area,\" a Palumbo representative claimed, \"as it is fundamental to the works being carried out by the dock yard.\" <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/98127/palumbo_group_and_aum_bump_heads_over_macina_parking_entrance_#.XbJDAG5FzIU|title=Palumbo Group and AUM bump heads over Macina parking entrance|work=[[Malta Today]]|date=20 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Speculations of a hotel development===\nThe planned extension of the Dock 1 facilities fuelled speculation that the Sadeen Group intends to declare the AUM project a failure and convert the site into a luxury hotel. A coalition of Cottonera residents and community groups \"expressed concern that the long-term objective of constructing a dormitory was to convert it to a hotel in a few years' time.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Micallef|first1=Keith|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/last-ditch-attempt-to-safeguard-skyline-from-american-university-malta.737569|title=Last ditch attempt to 'safeguard' skyline from American University Malta plans|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Students abscond to Europe===\nThe Maltese press revealed that nearly a third of the AUM's new students had absconded from Malta to mainland Europe, rather than remain in Malta to start their studies. \"In what may be a case of irregular migration,\" wrote Ivan Camilleri, Times of Malta journalist reporting on four Bangladeshi students who escaped to continental Europe, \"they are suspected to have used the Schengen visas they were granted on the strength of their student status to make their way to another EU country. The Schengen visa allows its holder free movement in 22 EU Member States and four other European countries.\" <ref>{{cite news|last1=Camilleri|first1=Ivan|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/american-university-students-disappear-before-reaching-campus.670306|title=Four American University students \u2018disappear\u2019 before reaching campus|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=11 February 2018}}</ref> In an interview with investigative journalist Lizzie Eldridge, Provost John Ryder admitted that foreign students had used the AUM as a launch board into Europe. Responding defensively, he acknowledged that the absconding students posed security risks (human trafficking and terrorism), but insisted that all were reported to Maltese immigration authorities.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Eldridge|first1=Lizzie|title=Interview: The Man who came from Baku (2)|url=https://manueldelia.com/2019/08/interview-the-man-who-came-in-from-baku-2/|website=manueldelia.com|date=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.aum.edu.mt/#Home Official website]\n\n{{Portal bar|Education|Malta|United States}}\n\n[[Category:Liberal arts colleges]]\n[[Category:Universities in Malta]]\n[[Category:Cospicua]]\n[[Category:Marsaskala]]\n[[Category:Proposed buildings and structures]]\n[[Category:Controversies in Malta]]\n[[Category:Environmental controversies]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2016]]\n[[Category:2016 establishments in Malta]]\n[[Category:2015 controversies]]\n[[Category:2016 controversies]]\n[[Category:2017 controversies]]\n[[Category:2018 controversies]]\n", "name_user": "BenBelkin101", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eControversies", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_University_of_Malta"}
